The '''Gateway Program''' is an ongoing expansion and renovation of the [[Northeast Corridor]] (NEC) rail line between [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]], and [[New York City]] along the [[Right-of-way (property access)|right-of-way]] between [[Newark Penn Station]] and [[New York Penn Station]]. The project is intended to build new rail bridges in the [[New Jersey Meadowlands]], dig a new set of tunnels under [[Bergen Hill]] ([[Hudson Palisades]]) and the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]], and rehabilitate the existing 1910 tunnel, all with the goal of doubling train capacity to four tracks along the right-of-way, since the current two-track rail line, used both by [[Amtrak]] and [[NJ Transit Rail Operations]] (NJT), has reached its full capacity of 24 trains per hour.<ref name="GPDC-Board-201701"/>

It was unveiled as the Gateway Project in 2011, one year after the cancellation of the somewhat similar [[Access to the Region's Core]] (ARC) project; the need for renovations only increased after [[Hurricane Sandy]] damaged the [[North River Tunnels]] the following year.<ref name=APNews-Nightmare-2014/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://prospect.org/article/gateway-nowhere-on-hudson |title=Gateway To Nowhere on the Hudson |last=Gurley |first=Gabrielle |date=January 22, 2018 |website=The American Prospect |access-date=September 12, 2018 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143036/https://prospect.org/health/gateway-nowhere-hudson/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Bazeley 2017" /> It took nearly a decade to line up funding and regulatory approval for the biggest component, the new Hudson River tunnel, which began construction in 2023 and is scheduled to open in 2035, with rehabilitation of the old tunnels to follow by 2038. Other components that will complete the full four-track buildout between Newark Penn Station and New York, including the Portal South bridge and replacement Sawtooth Bridges, await funding.

==Background==

===Right-of-way===
[[File:NY Tunnel Extension & Connections PRR 1912.jpg|thumb|New York Tunnel Extension, 1912]]
The right-of-way was originally developed by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] (PRR)<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40716FD345D12738DDDAD0994D1405B828CF1D3&scp=10&sq=Point%20No%20Point%20Pennsylvania%20Railroad&st=cse |title=The Pennsylvania's Great Hudson River Tunnel |last=Prout |first=H.G. |date=September 14, 1902 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=June 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628222139/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40716FD345D12738DDDAD0994D1405B828CF1D3&scp=10&sq=Point%20No%20Point%20Pennsylvania%20Railroad&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> in conjunction with the 1910 opening of [[Pennsylvania Station (1910)|New York's Pennsylvania Station]], which required the construction of the [[Portal Bridge]] over the Hackensack River, as well as the [[North River Tunnels]] under the [[Hudson Palisades]] and Hudson River.<ref name="cudahy"/>{{rp|37, 39}} The following year the [[Manhattan Transfer station]] was opened in the [[Kearny Meadows]] to allow changes between steam and electric locomotives. This station also provided for passenger transfers to/from its former main terminal at [[Exchange Place station (PRR)|Exchange Place]] in Jersey City or the [[Hudson and Manhattan Railroad]] (H&M), the forerunner of today's [[Port Authority Trans Hudson]] (PATH).<ref name="cudahy">{{Cite Cudahy-Hudson|mode=cs1}}</ref>{{rp|41–42}} The [[Dock Bridge]] over the Passaic River was opened in conjunction with the adjacent [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Newark Penn Station]] in 1935.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A13F9345C157A93C6A8178ED85F458385F9&scp=3&sq=newark+railroad&st=p |title=Newark Adopts Plans for New Rail Station; How Newark Railroad Station Will Look |date=May 14, 1931 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 21, 2011 |archive-date=November 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106071256/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A13F9345C157A93C6A8178ED85F458385F9&scp=3&sq=newark+railroad&st=p |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1935/03/24/archives/newark-dedicates-its-new-terminal-railroad-station-centre-link-in.html%26scp%3D7%26sq%3Dnewark+railroad%26st%3Dp |title=Newark Dedicates its New Terminal; Railroad Station, Centre Link in $42,000,000 Project, Is Opened to the Public |date=March 24, 1935 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 21, 2011 |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723070001/https://www.nytimes.com/1935/03/24/archives/newark-dedicates-its-new-terminal-railroad-station-centre-link-in.html%26scp%3D7%26sq%3Dnewark+railroad%26st%3Dp |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1937, the H&M was extended over a second span, making the transfer in the meadows redundant.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0B14FB3A541B728DDDA90A94DE405B878FF1D3 |title=New Station Open for Hudson Tubes |date=June 20, 1937 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 18, 2011 |page=1 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143036/https://www.nytimes.com/1937/06/20/archives/new-station-open-for-hudson-tubes-newark-terminal-is-shifted-from.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 1949, the PRR discontinued its [[List of ferries across the Hudson River to New York City|ferry system]] on the Hudson, and in 1961, it closed its Exchange Place station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.njcu.edu/programs/jchistory/Pages/E_Pages/Exchange_Place.htm |title=Exchange Place |last1=Karnoutsos |first1=Carmela |last2=Shalhoub |first2=Patrick |year=2007 |website=Jersey City Past and Present |publisher=New Jersey City University |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814221758/http://www.njcu.edu/programs/jchistory/Pages/E_Pages/Exchange_Place.htm |archive-date=August 14, 2004 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 16, 2011 }}</ref> In 1963, due to declining traffic and revenue, the PRR demolished the above-ground [[New York Penn Station]]. It retained its below-ground passenger concourses and waiting areas, and sold its [[air rights]], enabling construction of a new [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref name="Pennstation">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nyc-architecture.com/GON/GON004.htm |title=Penn Station |website=New York Architecture Images – gone |publisher=nyc-architecture.com |access-date=February 18, 2011 |archive-date=June 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604182354/http://www.nyc-architecture.com/GON/GON004.htm |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1967, the [[Aldene Plan]] was implemented, requiring the floundering [[Central Railroad of New Jersey]] (CNJ), [[Reading Railroad|Reading]] (RDG), and [[Lehigh Valley Railroad|Lehigh Valley]] (LV) railroads, to travel into Newark Penn while continuing service to New York Penn.<ref name=cudahy/>{{rp|61}}<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://www.arcadiapublsihing.com |title=Images of America: Railroads of Hoboken and Jersey City |last=French |first=Kenneth |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-7385-0966-2 |location=USA |page=30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801054035/http://arcadiapublsihing.com/ |archive-date=August 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Under continued financial pressure, the PRR merged with [[New York Central]] (NYC) in 1968, but the newly-formed [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] (PC) declared bankruptcy on June 21, 1970. In 1976, the PC long-distance service (including part of today's [[Northeast Corridor]] and [[Empire Corridor]]) was assumed by [[Amtrak]], which had been founded in 1971.<ref name="Amtrak brief">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbo.gov/doc.cfm?index=4571&type=0&sequence=3 |title=A Brief History of Amtrak |last=Pinkston |first=Elizabeth |date=2003 |website=U.S. Congressional Budget Office}}</ref> [[Conrail]] was created in 1976 to consolidate numerous Northeast private railroads, including commuter service on the CNJ and the LV.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.conrail.com/history.htm |title=A Brief History of Conrail |year=2003 |publisher=Consolidated Rail Corporation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121075513/http://conrail.com/history.htm |archive-date=November 21, 2010 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.american-rails.com/conrail.html |title=Conrail, The Consolidated Rail Corporation |publisher=American-Rails.com |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=March 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317225220/http://www.american-rails.com/conrail.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Conrail divested itself from passenger operations in 1983, and NJT assumed control.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9806E1DC1539F933A25751C0A960958260&scp=4&sq=Crash%20on%20New%20Jersey%20Tranist&st=cse |title=Crash on New Jersey Transit;Agency Had Enviable Safety Record |last=Pulley |first=Brett |date=February 10, 1996 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143035/https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/10/nyregion/crash-on-new-jersey-transit-the-railroad-agency-had-enviable-safety-record.html?scp=4&sq=Crash+on+New+Jersey+Tranist&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 1991, NJT opened the [[Waterfront Connection]], extending service on several non-electrified trains which had previously terminated at Newark Penn Station to Hoboken.<ref name="wtrfrntconnect">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE0D81731F933A2575AC0A967958260&scp=2&sq=Waterfront%20Connection%20New%20Jersey%20Transit&st=cse |title=Hoboken-Newark Rail Link Opens as Part of Multimillion-Dollar Expansion |last=Hanley |first=Robert |date=September 10, 1991 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 20, 2011 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143538/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/10/nyregion/hoboken-newark-rail-link-opens-as-part-of-multimillion-dollar-expansion.html?scp=2&sq=Waterfront+Connection+New+Jersey+Transit&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1996, NJT inaugurated [[Midtown Direct]] service, rerouting some trains from the west which previously terminated at [[Hoboken Terminal]] to New York Penn.<ref name="Allaboard">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9806E5D6163FF93BA35751C1A960958260&sec=&spon=&&scp=5&sq=Kearny%20connection&st=cse |title=All Aboard for New York, if There's Parking Near the Train |last=Chen |first=David W. |date=December 8, 1996 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143538/https://www.nytimes.com/1996/12/08/nyregion/all-aboard-for-new-york-if-there-s-parking-near-the-train.html?sec=&spon=&&scp=5&sq=Kearny+connection&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NJaddtrains">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE5D7173AF932A35756C0A967958260&scp=1&sq=Kearny%20connection&st=cse |title=New Jersey to Add Trains to Midtown |last=Hanley |first=Robert |date=May 1, 1991 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143536/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/01/nyregion/new-jersey-to-add-trains-to-midtown.html?scp=1&sq=Kearny+connection&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Secaucus Junction]] was opened in 2003, allowing passengers travelling from the north to transfer to [[Northeast Corridor Line]], [[North Jersey Coast Line]], or Midtown Direct trains, though not to Amtrak, which made no stops there. Between 1976 and 2010, the number of NJT weekday trains crossing the Hudson using the North River Tunnels (under contract with Amtrak<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/30/nyregion/new-jersey-s-amtrak-blues.html?scp=1&sq=New%20Jersey%27s%20Amtrak%20Blues&st=cse |title=New Jersey's Amtrak Blues |last=Sullivan |first=John |date=June 2, 2002 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 27, 2011 |archive-date=February 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201141103/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/30/nyregion/new-jersey-s-amtrak-blues.html?scp=1&sq=New%20Jersey%27s%20Amtrak%20Blues&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref>) increased from 147 to 438.<ref name="GatewayPDF" />

===Trans-Hudson crossings===
The Northeast Corridor is the most heavily traveled railway in the United States, and is the only rail line that travels under the Hudson River and through New York City.<ref>[https://nec.amtrak.com/news/gateway-program-development-corporation-releases-request-for-information-for-hudson-tunnel-project/ Request for Information for Hudson Tunnel Project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602194850/https://nec.amtrak.com/news/gateway-program-development-corporation-releases-request-for-information-for-hudson-tunnel-project/ |date=June 2, 2019 }}. Amtrak Northeast Corridor. August 10, 2017. Accessed February 10, 2019.</ref>  The other rail system crossing the Hudson was developed by the [[Hudson and Manhattan Railroad]], partially in conjunction with the PRR,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/09/04/105089674.pdf |title=By Way of Jersey |date=September 4, 1910 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 27, 2011 |archive-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210708003721/https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/09/04/105089674.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> and taken over by PANYNJ in 1962, who rebranded the H&M as the PATH, a rapid transit system.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/01/23/102744546.pdf |title=2 States Agree on Hudson Tubes and Trade Center; New York and Jersey Settle on Bill to Permit Port Authority Operation |last=Wright |first=George Cable |date=January 23, 1962 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> Direct trans-Hudson rail service to Lower Manhattan from Newark Penn is provided by PATH with additional terminals at [[World Trade Center station (PATH)|World Trade Center]] and [[33rd Street station (PATH)|Herald Square]] in Manhattan, and at Hoboken Terminal and [[Journal Square Transportation Center|Journal Square]] in Hudson County, New Jersey.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panynj.gov/path/maps.html |title=PATH map |publisher=Port Authority of New York and New Jersey |access-date=March 7, 2011 |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121050235/http://www.panynj.gov/path/maps.html |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1971 New Jersey Governor [[William T. Cahill]] proposed constructing another rail tunnel from [[Weehawken, New Jersey]], to 48th Street in Midtown Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/05/archives/cahill-asks-new-rail-tunnel-to-manhattan.html |title=Cahill Asks New Rail Tunnel to Manhattan |last=Sullivan |first=Ronald |date=February 5, 1971 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=April 9, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410002222/https://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/05/archives/cahill-asks-new-rail-tunnel-to-manhattan.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

There are three vehicular crossings of the lower Hudson River.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/11/opinion/nyregionopinions/CIcongest.html?scp=40&sq=Amtrak+new+jersey&st=nyt |title=Time to Move on Hudson Tunnel |last=Editorial |date=November 17, 2007 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 27, 2011 |archive-date=April 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409233742/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/11/opinion/nyregionopinions/CIcongest.html?scp=40&sq=Amtrak+new+jersey&st=nyt |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holland Tunnel]], opened in 1927, is minimally used for public transportation and connects Jersey City, New Jersey, to lower Manhattan. The [[George Washington Bridge]], opened in 1931, is used by suburban buses to [[George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal|GWB Bus Terminal]], and connects [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]], to upper Manhattan. Its lower level, opened in 1962, is the last new river crossing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://policy.rutgers.edu/vtc/tod/newsletter/vol5-num1/ARC.html |title=Transit Friendly Development |date=May 2009 |publisher=Voorhees Transportation Center/Rutgers University |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720041254/http://policy.rutgers.edu/vtc/tod/newsletter/vol5-num1/ARC.html |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 7, 2011 }}</ref> The [[Lincoln Tunnel]], composed of three tubes opened in 1937, 1945, and 1954, connects Weehawken, New Jersey, to Midtown Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://media.nj.com/ledgerupdates_impact/photo/hudson-river-tunnel-historyjpg-41ba3e9d7448b3e1.jpg |title=History Across the Hudson |last=Port Authority of New York and New Jersey |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714184902/http://media.nj.com/ledgerupdates_impact/photo/hudson-river-tunnel-historyjpg-41ba3e9d7448b3e1.jpg |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 15, 2011 |newspaper=The Star Ledger }}</ref> More than 6,000 bus trips are made through the tunnel and bus terminal daily.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/135160048_Lawmakers_urge_PA_to_reduce_bus_delays.html |title=Lawmakers urge PA to reduce bus delays |last=Boburg |first=Shawn |date=December 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115200753/http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/135160048_Lawmakers_urge_PA_to_reduce_bus_delays.html |archive-date=January 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |access-date=December 14, 2011 |newspaper=The Record }}</ref>    Its eastern terminus is connected via ramps to the [[Port Authority Bus Terminal]], the gateway for most [[List of New Jersey Transit bus routes (100–199)|NJT bus traffic]] entering Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panynj.gov/bus-terminals/pabt-history.html |title=Port Authority Bus Terminal History |publisher=Port Authority of New York and New Jersey |access-date=March 7, 2011 |archive-date=June 3, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603091437/http://www.panynj.gov/bus-terminals/pabt-history.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite the [[Lincoln Tunnel XBL]] (express bus lane) during the morning peak there are often long delays due to traffic congestion and the limited capacity of the bus terminal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tstc.org/press/2009/051409_bus_report.html |title=New Report and Website Offer Speedier Bus Commute Across the Hudson River Report calls for Port Authority to prioritize bus trips for 100 million annual passengers |date=May 14, 2009 |publisher=Tri-state Transportation Campaign |access-date=April 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114044853/http://tstc.org/press/2009/051409_bus_report.html |archive-date=November 14, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.tstc.org/2011/04/28/nj-transportation-funding-plan-would-shortchange-bus-riders/ |title=NJ Transportation Funding Plan Would Shortchange Bus Riders |last=Chernetz |first=Janna |date=April 28, 2011 |publisher=Mobilizing the Region |access-date=April 29, 2011 |archive-date=September 13, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913164658/http://blog.tstc.org/2011/04/28/nj-transportation-funding-plan-would-shortchange-bus-riders/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703916004576271150274132500 |title=Bus Terminal Hits Limit |last=Grossman |first=Andrew |date=April 19, 2011 |access-date=April 29, 2011 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |archive-date=June 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611090020/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703916004576271150274132500 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Access to the Region's Core===
{{main|Access to the Region's Core}}

[[File:NJT owned factory-grounds at western portal of ARC-Gateway tunnel-Tonnelle Ave-North Bergen.jpg|thumb|Site of the western portal of the tunnel in North Bergen at Tonnelle Avenue]]Launched in 1995 by PANYNJ, NJT, and MTA, Access to the Region's Core (ARC) was a [[Major Investment Study]] that looked at public transportation ideas for the New York metropolitan area. It found that long-term goals would best be met by better connections to and in-between the region's major rail stations in Midtown Manhattan, Penn Station and Grand Central Terminal.<ref name="ARCMISsummary">{{Cite web |url=http://www.arctunnel.com/pdf/library/ARC_MIS_Summary_Report.pdf |title=Access to the Region's Core Major Investment Study Summary Report 2003 |year=2003 |publisher=arctunnel.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429194828/http://arctunnel.com/pdf/library/ARC_MIS_Summary_Report.pdf |archive-date=April 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 6, 2011 }}</ref> The [[East Side Access]] project, including tunnels under the East River and the East Side of Manhattan, was completed in early 2023; some [[Long Island Rail Road|LIRR]] traffic has been diverted to [[Grand Central Madison|Grand Central]], freeing up track slots at Penn Station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/151214_0930_LIRR.pdf#page=17 |title=Long Island Committee Meeting December 2015 |date=December 14, 2015 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225054749/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/151214_0930_LIRR.pdf#page=17 |archive-date=February 25, 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 17, 2016 }}</ref><ref name="ABC7 New York 20230227">{{cite web | title=LIRR full service begins Monday, 2/27, at Grand Central Madison; train schedules to change | website=ABC7 New York | date=February 27, 2023 | url=https://abc7ny.com/lirr-train-schedule-grand-central-madison-opens/12887154/ | access-date=February 27, 2023 | archive-date=September 25, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240925024805/https://abc7ny.com/lirr-train-schedule-grand-central-madison-opens/12887154/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Castillo 20230227">{{cite web | last=Castillo | first=Alfonso A. | title=East Side Access completed, LIRR riders get full service to Grand Central Madison Monday | website=Newsday | date=February 26, 2023 | url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/transportation/grand-central-madison-east-side-access-lirr-gpwsijw3 | access-date=February 27, 2023 | archive-date=February 26, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230226233806/https://www.newsday.com/long-island/transportation/grand-central-madison-east-side-access-lirr-gpwsijw3 | url-status=live }}</ref>

The Trans-Hudson Express Tunnel or [[THE Tunnel]], which later took on the name of the study itself, was meant to address the western, or Hudson River, crossing. Engineering studies determined that structural interferences made a new terminal connected to Grand Central or the current Penn Station unfeasible and its final design involved [[boring (earth)|boring]] under the current rail yard to a new deep cavern terminal station under 34th Street.<ref name="FEISXS">New Jersey Transit (October 2008). Newark, NJ. [http://www.arctunnel.com/pdf/library/0_5_executive_summary_feis.pdf "Access to the Region's Core: Final Environmental Impact Study."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807203256/http://www.arctunnel.com/pdf/library/0_5_executive_summary_feis.pdf |date=August 7, 2011 }} Executive Summary.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newurbannetwork.com/news-opinion/blogs/ian-rassmussen/13726/when-environmental-impact-statement-takes-lifetime |title=When an Environmental Impact Statement takes a lifetime |last=Rassmussen |first=Ian |date=December 15, 2010 |publisher=New Urban News |access-date=March 7, 2012 |quote=The story of ARC began in 1995 with the start of a "Major Investment Study" that reviewed 137 alternative transportation improvements that would get commuters from central and northern New Jersey out of their cars, and into Manhattan faster, cheaper, and with less harm to the environment. After four years of study, the list was narrowed down to a few finalists in 1999. From 1999 to 2003, the feasibility of each of those plans (exactly where the tracks would be laid, and how they would connect to Penn Station) was studied, and the ultimate plan ironed out. From 2003 to 2009, the final plan — two new rail tunnels leading to a new lower level of Penn Station — was the subject of an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS). |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714175322/http://newurbannetwork.com/news-opinion/blogs/ian-rassmussen/13726/when-environmental-impact-statement-takes-lifetime |url-status=live }}</ref> While Amtrak had acknowledged that the region represented a bottleneck in the national system and had originally planned to complete work by 2040,<ref name="AMTKNJT">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/similar_hudson_river_tunnel_pr.html |title=Hudson River tunnel project proposed by Amtrak, NJ Transit would take decades to complete |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=November 8, 2010 |work=The Star Ledger |access-date=February 27, 2011 |archive-date=January 19, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119183229/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/similar_hudson_river_tunnel_pr.html |url-status=live }}</ref> its timetable for beginning the project was advanced in part due to the cancellation of ARC, a project similar in scope, but with differences in design.<ref name="Fleisher">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704422204576130673174593178 |title=Amtrak's Plan For New Tunnel Gains Support |last1=Fleisher |first1=Liza |last2=Grossman |first2=Andrew |date=February 8, 2011 |access-date=February 8, 2011 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |archive-date=July 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035617/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704422204576130673174593178 |url-status=live }}</ref> That project, which did not include direct Amtrak participation,<ref name="AMTKNJT" /><ref name="break down">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/amtrak_nj_transit_break_off_ta.html |title=Amtrak, NJ Transit break off talks on reviving ARC Hudson River rail tunnel |date=November 12, 2010 |access-date=March 7, 2011 |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |archive-date=December 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219160318/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/amtrak_nj_transit_break_off_ta.html |url-status=live }}</ref> was cancelled in October 2010 by New Jersey governor [[Chris Christie]], who cited potential cost overruns.<ref name="ARCcancel">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/08/nyregion/08tunnel.html |title=Christie Halts Train Tunnel, Citing Its Cost |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=October 7, 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 8, 2010 |archive-date=September 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903010718/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/08/nyregion/08tunnel.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Amtrak briefly engaged the governor in attempt to revive the ARC Tunnel and use preliminary work done for it, but those negotiations soon broke down.<ref name="Frassinelli" /><ref name="AMTKNJT" /><ref name="break down" /> Amtrak said it was not interested in purchasing any of the work.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/jjournal/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-5%2F1289633139318930.xml&coll=3 |title=Amtrak: no interest in Hudson tunnel |date=November 13, 2010 |access-date=March 13, 2011 |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |archive-date=June 29, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629212559/http://www.nj.com/news/jjournal/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-5%2F1289633139318930.xml&coll=3 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Senator Menendez later said some preparatory work done for ARC may be used for the new project.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mycentraljersey.com/article/20110207/NJNEWS10/110207021/1254/NJSPORTS |title=Amtrak plans new tunnel under Hudson River |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=February 8, 2011 |publisher=mycentraljersey.com |access-date=February 21, 2011 |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714150831/http://www.mycentraljersey.com/article/20110207/NJNEWS10/110207021/1254/NJSPORTS |url-status=live }}</ref> Costs for the project were $117 million for preliminary engineering, $126 million for final design, $15 million for construction and $178 million real estate property rights ($28 million in New Jersey and $150 million in New York City). Additionally, a $161 million partially refundable pre-payment of insurance premiums was also made.<ref name="statewants">{{Cite web |url=http://www.northjersey.com/recap/117040328_State_wants_refund_for__161_9M_tunnel_insurance.html |title=State wants refund for $161.9M tunnel insurance |last=Pillets |first=Jeff |date=February 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926134017/http://www.northjersey.com/recap/117040328_State_wants_refund_for__161_9M_tunnel_insurance.html |archive-date=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 14, 2011 |newspaper=The Record }}</ref>

==Plans, construction and project status==

===Announcement and initial phases===
{{GeoGroup}}
In the aftermath of New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]]'s cancelation of the [[Access to the Region's Core|ARC tunnel]], the Gateway Project was unveiled on February 7, 2011, by [[Amtrak]] President [[Joseph H. Boardman]] and New Jersey Senators [[Frank Lautenberg]] and [[Robert Menendez]].<ref name="McGeehan">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/08/nyregion/08tunnel.html |title=With One Plan for a Hudson Tunnel Dead, Senators Offer Another Option |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=February 7, 2011 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143035/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/08/nyregion/08tunnel.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/020811_Amtrak_president_details_Gateway_Project_at_Rutgers_lecture.html |title=Amtrak president details Gateway Project at Rutgers lecture |last=Rouse |first=Karen |date=February 8, 2011 |work=Bergen Record |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209045627/http://www.northjersey.com/news/020811_Amtrak_president_details_Gateway_Project_at_Rutgers_lecture.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NJAmtrak">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/02/nj_senators_to_announce_new_co.html |title=N.J. senators, Amtrak official to announce new commuter train tunnel project across the Hudson |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=February 6, 2011 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=February 7, 2011 |archive-date=February 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110207232224/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/02/nj_senators_to_announce_new_co.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="GatewayPDF">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lautenberg.senate.gov/assets/Gateway.pdf |title=Gateway Project |date=February 2011 |publisher=Amtrak |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517075834/http://www.lautenberg.senate.gov/assets/Gateway.pdf |archive-date=May 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> Some previously planned improvements were included in the project to increase capacity across the New Jersey bottleneck of the [[Northeast Corridor]], as ARC was meant to, but the new plan would include two new Hudson tunnels that would connect directly to Penn Station, their introduction would allow for the refurbishment of the existing [[North River Tunnels]], and Amtrak would now take the lead in seeking financing.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Lautenberg, Menendez Join Amtrak to Announce New Trans-Hudson Gateway Tunnel Project |date=February 7, 2011 |publisher=Lautenberg/US Senate press release |url=http://lautenberg.senate.gov/newsroom/record.cfm?id=330933 |access-date=February 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721062423/http://lautenberg.senate.gov/newsroom/record.cfm?id=330933 |archive-date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref name="Frassinelli">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/02/gov_christie_approves_of_new_g.html |title=Gov. Christie says new Gateway tunnel plan addresses his ARC project cost concerns |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=February 8, 2011 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=February 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210025815/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/02/gov_christie_approves_of_new_g.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="AMTKproposes">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/07/AR2011020703557.html |title=Amtrak Proposes $13.5 Billion New Jersey Rail Project |last=Caruso |first=Lisa |date=February 7, 2011 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=June 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230417/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/07/AR2011020703557.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

By late 2011, two associated projects were considered part of the Gateway modernization and were underway: the replacement of the [[Portal Bridge]] over the [[Hackensack River]], and the development of [[Moynihan Train Hall]] in [[Manhattan]]. [[Environmental impact statement]]s had been completed, and the design and engineering of the new bridges had begun.<ref name="Portal Bridge Capacity Enhancement">{{Cite web |url=http://www.portalbridgenec.com |title=Portal Bridge Capacity Enhancement |publisher=Amtrak, New Jersey Transit, U.S Department of Transportation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208112822/http://portalbridgenec.com/ |archive-date=February 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref name="approval">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/01/nyregion/01bridge.html |title=Approval Given for New Jersey Rail Bridges |last=Belsen |first=Ken |date=December 31, 2008 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 8, 2011 |archive-date=April 10, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410054102/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/01/nyregion/01bridge.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="nj.com">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/01/nj_transit_board_announces_385.html |title=NJ Transit announces $38.5M for Portal Bridge project, names executive director |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=January 28, 2010 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=February 8, 2011 |archive-date=June 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001153/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/01/nj_transit_board_announces_385.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Whiten">{{Cite web |url=http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2010/02/08/advocates-want-bikeped-path-as-part-of-portal-bridge-project/ |title=Advocates Want Bike/Ped Path as Part of Portal Bridge Project |last=Whiten |first=Jon |date=February 8, 2010 |publisher=Jersey City Independent |access-date=February 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711102814/http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2010/02/08/advocates-want-bikeped-path-as-part-of-portal-bridge-project/ |archive-date=July 11, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="finalpiece">{{Cite web |url=http://fastlane.dot.gov/2010/10/tiger-grant-provides-final-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-moynihan-station.html |title=TIGER grant provides final piece of the Moynihan Station funding puzzle |date=October 19, 2010 |publisher=United States Department of Transportation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124041110/http://fastlane.dot.gov/2010/10/tiger-grant-provides-final-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-moynihan-station.html |archive-date=November 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 9, 2011 }}</ref> The ceremonial groundbreaking of the first phase of conversion of the [[James Farley Post Office]] into the Moynihan Train Hall took place in October 2010,<ref name="Bagli">{{Cite news |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/a-ceremonial-start-for-moynihan-station/?scp=1&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |title=A Ceremonial Start for Moynihan Station |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |date=October 18, 2010 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714220451/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/a-ceremonial-start-for-moynihan-station/?scp=1&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> partially funded by the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/ARRAPortalBridgeCertification.pdf |title=The American Recovery and Reinvestment Act |publisher=Njtransit.com |access-date=May 7, 2015 |archive-date=February 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206093043/http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/ARRAPortalBridgeCertification.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://transportation.house.gov/uploadedfiles/documents/2013-06-07-mcdonald.pdf |title=Written Testimony of Joan McDonald |date=June 7, 2013 |access-date=December 11, 2013 |archive-date=September 19, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919072251/http://transportation.house.gov/uploadedfiles/documents/2013-06-07-mcdonald.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/recovery/sponsors/tiger |title=Transportation Investment Generating Economic Recovery (TIGER) |date=February 6, 2015 |website=NY DOT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206114929/https://www.dot.ny.gov/recovery/sponsors/tiger |archive-date=February 6, 2015 |url-status=live |access-date=October 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-on-new-hudson-train-tunnels-chugs-along-1422240370 |title=Work on New Hudson Train Tunnels Chugs Along |last=Tangel |first=Andrew |date=February 1, 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=February 4, 2015 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143039/https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-on-new-hudson-train-tunnels-chugs-along-1422240370 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Projected costs ===
In 2011, the project was projected to take $13.5 billion and nine years, and Amtrak asked that $1.3 billion in [[United States Department of Transportation]] funding for NEC rail corridor improvements be allocated to Gateway.<ref name="Amtrakseeks">{{Cite web |url=http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/BlobServer?blobcol=urldata&blobtable=MungoBlobs&blobkey=id&blobwhere=1249224538367&blobheader=application%2Fpdf&blobhead |title=Amtrak Seeks $1.3 billion for Gateway Project and Next-Generation High-Speed Rail on NEC |date=April 4, 2011 |publisher=Amtrak |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503205942/http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/BlobServer?blobcol=urldata&blobtable=MungoBlobs&blobkey=id&blobwhere=1249224538367&blobheader=application%2Fpdf&blobhead |archive-date=May 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=April 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref name="AMTKseeking">{{Cite web |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/state/040411_Amtrak_seeking_13B_for_Hudson_River_tunnel_planning_bridge_replacement.html |title=Amtrak seeking $1.3B for Hudson River tunnel planning, bridge replacement |last=Jackson |first=Herb |date=April 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516141417/http://www.northjersey.com/news/state/040411_Amtrak_seeking_13B_for_Hudson_River_tunnel_planning_bridge_replacement.html |archive-date=May 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=April 10, 2011 |newspaper=The Record}}
</ref> In November, Congress allocated $15 million for initial engineering work.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/11/engineering_work_to_begin_on_g.html |title=Engineering work to begin on Gateway train tunnel under Hudson River, Congress approves $15M for project |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=November 18, 2011 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=November 22, 2011 |archive-date=November 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120173831/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/11/engineering_work_to_begin_on_g.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/state/The_Source_blog_Senate_clears_15M_for_Amtrak_Gateway_tunnel_planning.html |title=Senate OKs $15M in design funds for NJ-NY tunnel |last=Boburg |first=Shawn |date=November 2, 2011 |work=The Record |access-date=November 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014428/http://www.northjersey.com/news/state/The_Source_blog_Senate_clears_15M_for_Amtrak_Gateway_tunnel_planning.html |archive-date=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://njtoday.net/2011/11/02/u-s-senate-approves-funding-for-nj-ny-rail-tunnel-design// |title=U.S. Senate Approves Funding For NJ-NY Rail Tunnel Design |date=November 2, 2011 |access-date=November 2, 2011 |publisher=NJToday.com |archive-date=June 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609133030/http://njtoday.net/2011/11/02/u-s-senate-approves-funding-for-nj-ny-rail-tunnel-design/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2012, [[United States Senate Appropriations Subcommittee on Transportation, Housing and Urban Development, and Related Agencies|a U.S. Senate subcommittee]] proposed another $20 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/04/20/senate-committee-oks-20-million-for-gateway-tunnel-project/ |title=Senate Committee OKs $20 Million For Gateway Tunnel Project |date=April 4, 2012 |publisher=CBS |access-date=July 20, 2012 |archive-date=July 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720013728/http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/04/20/senate-committee-oks-20-million-for-gateway-tunnel-project/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=Lautenberg, Menendez Announce $20 Million For Gateway Tunnel Project Approved In Senate Committee |date=April 19, 2012 |publisher=Senate.gov |url=http://lautenberg.senate.gov/newsroom/record.cfm?id=336577 |access-date=July 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509093326/http://lautenberg.senate.gov/newsroom/record.cfm?id=336577 |archive-date=May 9, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hudsonreporter.com/view/full_story/18302813/article--Senate-Appropriations-Committee-approves--20-million-for-Gateway-Tunnel-?instance=home_Most_popular |title=Senate Appropriations Committee approves $20 million for Gateway Tunnel |date=April 20, 2012 |access-date=July 23, 2012 |newspaper=Hudson Reporter |archive-date=May 5, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505023808/http://hudsonreporter.com/view/full_story/18302813/article--Senate-Appropriations-Committee-approves--20-million-for-Gateway-Tunnel-?instance=home_Most_popular |url-status=dead}}</ref> In September 2012, Schumer estimated that the project would need $20 million in 2013 and $100 million in 2014 to keep it from dying.<ref name="action">{{Cite web |url=http://transportationnation.org/2012/09/28/schumer-fast-action-needed-for-new-amtrak-tunnel/ |title=Sen. Schumer: Fast Action Needed for New Amtrak Tunnel |last=Marritz |first=Ilya |date=September 28, 2012 |publisher=Transportation Nation |access-date=October 3, 2012 |archive-date=October 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001025902/http://transportationnation.org/2012/09/28/schumer-fast-action-needed-for-new-amtrak-tunnel/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

After [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, Amtrak requested $276 million from Congress to upgrade damaged infrastructure that would also eventually support trains running along the new Gateway Project right-of-way.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/Amtrak_asks_Congress_for_emergency_funding_for_flood_protection.html |title=Amtrak asks Congress for emergency funding for flood protection |last=Rouse |first=Karen |date=December 6, 2012 |work=The Record |access-date=November 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213223146/http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/Amtrak_asks_Congress_for_emergency_funding_for_flood_protection.html |archive-date=December 13, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/transportation-nation/amtrak-asks-subsidies-wake-hurricane-sandy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525072415/http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/transportation-nation/amtrak-asks-subsidies-wake-hurricane-sandy |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 25, 2013 |title=Amtrak asks for subsidies in wake of Hurricane Sandy |last=Goldmark |first=Alex |date=December 13, 2012 |publisher=Transportation Nation |access-date=December 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/1019/981/Amtrak-CEO-Boardman-Senate-Commerce-testimony-Dec-06-2012.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218180811/http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/1019/981/Amtrak-CEO-Boardman-Senate-Commerce-testimony-Dec-06-2012.pdf |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |title=Testimony of Joseph H. Boardman... Hearing "Superstorm Sandy: the Devastating Impact on the Nation's Largest Transportation Systems" |date=December 6, 2012 |publisher=Amtrak |access-date=January 25, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Congress did not provide funding in its Sandy relief legislation,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/01/obama_signs_50b_sandy_relief_b.html#incart_river_default |title=President Obama signs $50B Sandy relief bill |date=January 29, 2013 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=January 29, 2013 |agency=Associated Press |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216092144/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/01/obama_signs_50b_sandy_relief_b.html#incart_river_default |url-status=live }}</ref> but the U.S. Department of Transportation provided $185 million from its own Sandy relief and resiliency funds to build the "tunnel box" under the [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards]] redevelopment project and rebuild an overlapping Maintenance of Equipment building for the [[Long Island Rail Road]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/930/618/Amtrak-Hudson-Yards-Ceremony-ATK-13-105.pdf |title=Construction begins to preserve possible pathway of new train tunnels into penn station new york |date=September 13, 2013 |access-date=November 11, 2013 |publisher=Amtrak |archive-date=December 3, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004430/http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/930/618/Amtrak-Hudson-Yards-Ceremony-ATK-13-105.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Development corporation===
In November 2015, the creation of the Gateway Development Corporation was announced by Amtrak, U.S. Senators [[Cory Booker]] and [[Chuck Schumer]], and Governors Christie and [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.northjersey.com/cm/2.1593/news/officials-corporation-will-oversee-new-hudson-rail-tunnel-feds-will-split-cost-1.1454035 |title=Officials: Corporation will oversee new Hudson rail tunnel; feds will split cost |last=Maag |first=Christopher |date=November 12, 2015 |website=NorthJersey.com |access-date=March 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323233151/http://archive.northjersey.com/news/officials-corporation-will-oversee-new-hudson-rail-tunnel-feds-will-split-cost-1.1454035 |archive-date=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/11/booker_brokers_deal_on_entity_to_oversee_gateway_t.html |title=Feds agree to fund half of new Hudson rail tunnels, Booker says |date=November 12, 2015 |last=Higgs |first=Larry |website=NJ.com |access-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322205623/http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/11/booker_brokers_deal_on_entity_to_oversee_gateway_t.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The corporation would oversee planning, environmental, design, engineering, and construction work, and seek federal grants and loans. Its board was composed of [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] board members, the USDOT, and Amtrak, while its staff consisted of PANYNJ and Amtrak employees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/12/nyregion/corporation-to-oversee-new-hudson-rail-tunnel-with-us-and-amtrak-financing-half.html |title=Corporation to Oversee New Hudson Rail Tunnel, With U.S. and Amtrak Financing Half |last=Fitzsimmons |first=Emma G. |date=November 11, 2015 |website=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-date=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404044056/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/12/nyregion/corporation-to-oversee-new-hudson-rail-tunnel-with-us-and-amtrak-financing-half.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.northjersey.com/cm/2.1593/news/latest-plan-for-hudson-rail-tunnel-draws-questions-about-cost-accountability-1.1454391 |title=Signs of progress emerge on Hudson rail tunnel plan, but concern persists on finding $20B to fund it |last=Maag |first=Christopher |date=November 12, 2015 |website=NorthJersey.com |access-date=March 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323143315/http://archive.northjersey.com/news/latest-plan-for-hudson-rail-tunnel-draws-questions-about-cost-accountability-1.1454391 |archive-date=March 23, 2017}}</ref>

In December 2015, federal legislation was introduced to allow Amtrak to operate the NEC as a financially separate entity that could invest profits from the line into its infrastructure. The legislation also provided for more low-interest loans through changes in the [[Railroad Rehabilitation and Improvement Financing]] and Capital Investment Grant (New Starts) federal funding programs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.booker.senate.gov/?p=press_release&id=337 |title=Booker, Schumer Menendez, Amtrak Chair Announce Breakthroughs Achieved in Just-Passed Transportation Bill that Provides Clear Path to Federal Funding for Gateway Tunnel |date=December 7, 2015 |access-date=March 25, 2016 |publisher=www.booker.senate.gov |archive-date=April 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408061218/https://www.booker.senate.gov/?p=press_release&id=337 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2016, Amtrak and PANYNJ committed $35 million each for design and engineering work.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2016/03/new_hudson_river_rail_tunnels_take_big_step_forward.html |title=New Hudson River rail tunnels take big step forward |date=March 23, 2016 |last=Higgs |first=Larry |website=NJ.com |access-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-date=May 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501211219/http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2016/03/new_hudson_river_rail_tunnels_take_big_step_forward.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The group met for the first time on January 12, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2017/01/gateway_tunnel_financing_group_sets_stage_for_gett.html |title=Group starts funding effort for new Hudson River tunnels |date=January 12, 2017 |last=Higgs |first=Larry |website=NJ.com |access-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-date=May 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510173336/http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2017/01/gateway_tunnel_financing_group_sets_stage_for_gett.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nec.amtrak.com/content/notice-special-public-meeting-gateway-program-development-corporation |title=Notice of Special Public Meeting of the Gateway Program Development Corporation |publisher=Amtrak |language=en |access-date=July 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019105948/http://nec.amtrak.com/content/notice-special-public-meeting-gateway-program-development-corporation |archive-date=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On June 30, 2017, the U.S. Department of Transportation sent a letter to the Gateway Development Corporation permanently withdrawing from its board of trustees.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Davis |first=Jeff |date=July 1, 2017 |url=https://www.enotrans.org/article/usdot-withdraws-gateway-corporation/ |title=USDOT Withdraws From Gateway Corporation |website=The Eno Center for Transportation |access-date=October 26, 2017 |archive-date=October 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026213832/https://www.enotrans.org/article/usdot-withdraws-gateway-corporation/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortly afterward, the draft Environmental Impact Study for the project was issued.<ref name="Bazeley 2017">{{Cite web |url=https://www.amny.com/transit/hudson-tunnel-project-cost-projected-at-12-9-billion-1.13785636 |title=The Hudson Tunnel Project is expected to cost $12.9 billion |last=Bazeley |first=Alex |date=July 6, 2017 |website=am New York |access-date=May 7, 2018 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507222301/https://www.amny.com/transit/hudson-tunnel-project-cost-projected-at-12-9-billion-1.13785636 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Blocked by first Trump administration===
The [[Obama administration|administration]] of President [[Barack Obama]] called Gateway the most vital piece of infrastructure that needs to be built in the United States,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/08/nyregion/obama-administration-urges-quick-action-on-hudson-river-rail-tunnels.html |title=Obama Administration Urges Fast Action on New Hudson River Rail Tunnels |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=May 7, 2015 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=May 12, 2015 |archive-date=May 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519031012/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/08/nyregion/obama-administration-urges-quick-action-on-hudson-river-rail-tunnels.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and in a September 2015 joint letter, New Jersey Governor Chris Christie and New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] offered to pay half of the project's cost if the federal government picked up the rest.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/09/christie_cuomo_ask_obama_for_money_to_build_new_rail_tunnel_pledge_state_funds.html |title=Christie, Cuomo ask Obama for money to build new rail tunnel, pledge state funds |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=September 15, 2015 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=September 16, 2015 |archive-date=September 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918010630/http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/09/christie_cuomo_ask_obama_for_money_to_build_new_rail_tunnel_pledge_state_funds.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/nyregion/cuomo-and-christie-say-states-can-pay-half-of-hudson-rail-tunnel-project.html |title=Cuomo and Christie Say States Can Pay Half of Hudson Rail Tunnel Project |last=Fitzsimmons |first=Emma G. |date=September 16, 2015 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=September 16, 2015 |archive-date=September 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918201411/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/nyregion/cuomo-and-christie-say-states-can-pay-half-of-hudson-rail-tunnel-project.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/christie-cuomo-ask-obama-to-split-hudson-river-tunnel-costs-1442343768 |title=Christie, Cuomo Ask Obama to Split Hudson River Tunnel Costs |last=Tangle |first=Andrew |date=September 15, 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=September 16, 2015 |archive-date=September 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915220452/http://www.wsj.com/articles/christie-cuomo-ask-obama-to-split-hudson-river-tunnel-costs-1442343768 |url-status=live }}</ref> After President [[Donald Trump]] took office, however, his [[First presidency of Donald Trump|administration]] began to cast doubt on funding the project, as Trump suggested defunding the [[Federal Transit Administration]]'s New Starts program for all new projects,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/17/03/19/trump-infrastructure-flip-fop-could-put-gateway-tunnel-project-in-peril/ |title=Trump Infrastructure Flip-Flop Could Put Gateway Tunnel Project in Peril |last=Reitmeyer |first=John |date=March 20, 2017 |website=NJ Spotlight |access-date=March 22, 2017 |archive-date=March 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323013618/http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/17/03/19/trump-infrastructure-flip-fop-could-put-gateway-tunnel-project-in-peril/ |url-status=live }}</ref> despite his own [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Secretary of Transportation]] [[Elaine Chao]] calling the project "an absolute priority".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/05/watch_trump_transportation_official_tells_booker_that_gateway_is_absolute_priority.html |title=Trump transportation chief calls Gateway tunnel 'absolute priority' |last=Salant |first=Jonathon D. |date=May 17, 2017 |access-date=May 18, 2017 |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |archive-date=May 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523031805/http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/05/watch_trump_transportation_official_tells_booker_that_gateway_is_absolute_priority.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In September 2017, $900 million was allocated for the project in a House of Representatives spending bill,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/09/how_did_gateway_fare_in_house_spending_bill.html |title=What House just did with spending on Gateway Tunnel for new rail lines to NYC |website=NJ.com |date=September 15, 2017 |last=Salant |first=Jonathan D. |access-date=October 26, 2017 |archive-date=October 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019230310/http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/09/how_did_gateway_fare_in_house_spending_bill.html |url-status=live }}</ref> but under pressure from Trump, 155 Republican and four Democratic representatives co-sponsored a proposed amendment to remove the funding.<ref name="NJcom-Sandy-Harvey-funds-2017">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/09/will_house_republicans_take_away_sandy_funds_to_he.html |title=Will House Republicans take away Sandy funds after helping Harvey victims? |last=Salant |first=Jonathan D. |date=September 6, 2017 |website=NJ.com |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304113508/http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/09/will_house_republicans_take_away_sandy_funds_to_he.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="trump pushes">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/trump-pushes-republicans-to-oppose-crucial-new-york-new-jersey-tunnel-project/2018/03/02/06987446-1e6c-11e8-9de1-147dd2df3829_story.html |title=Trump pushes Republicans to oppose crucial New York-New Jersey tunnel project |last1=DeBonis |first1=Mike |date=March 2, 2018 |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=March 4, 2018 |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304031805/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/trump-pushes-republicans-to-oppose-crucial-new-york-new-jersey-tunnel-project/2018/03/02/06987446-1e6c-11e8-9de1-147dd2df3829_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 29, 2017, multiple news sources published a letter from a Trump administration FTA official who stated that the Gateway Program was a "local" project, putting federal funding for the project in doubt.<ref name="fox171231">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-pulls-brakes-on-13b-obama-backed-rail-tunnel-plan |title=Trump pulls brakes on $13B Obama-backed rail-tunnel plan |last1=Betz |first1=Bradford |date=December 31, 2017 |access-date=December 31, 2017 |publisher=Fox News |archive-date=December 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231073123/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/12/31/trump-pulls-brakes-on-13b-obama-backed-rail-tunnel-plan.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="cny171229">{{cite news |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20171229/POLITICS/171229921/trump-administration-kills-gateway-tunnel-deal |title=Trump administration kills Gateway tunnel deal |last1=Bredderman |first1=Will |date=December 29, 2017 |access-date=December 31, 2017 |work=Crain's New York Business |archive-date=December 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231070253/http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20171229/POLITICS/171229921/trump-administration-kills-gateway-tunnel-deal |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2018, Trump directly pressured Republican House Speaker [[Paul Ryan]] to oppose federal funding for the Gateway Program in the omnibus spending bill that was then being worked on.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2018/03/03/dems-fume-over-trumps-push-to-cut-funds-for-gateway-project/ |title=Dems fume over Trump's push to cut funds for Gateway project |date=March 3, 2018 |last1=Hogan |first1=Gynne |last2=Linge |first2=Mary Kay |work=New York Post |access-date=March 4, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-date=March 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303230642/https://nypost.com/2018/03/03/dems-fume-over-trumps-push-to-cut-funds-for-gateway-project/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="trump pushes" /> When the [[Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2018|Consolidated Appropriations Act]] was signed on March 23, 2018, it provided $2.9 billion to discretionary grant programs,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://policy.house.gov/legislative/bills/house-amendment-senate-amendment-hr1625-consolidated-appropriations-act-2018 |title=House Amendment to the Senate Amendment to H.R.1625, Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2018 |date=March 22, 2018 |website=Republican Policy Committee |access-date=March 25, 2018 |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326142403/https://policy.house.gov/legislative/bills/house-amendment-senate-amendment-hr1625-consolidated-appropriations-act-2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Bloomberg.com">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/new-york-new-jersey-rail-project-said-to-get-some-money-in-deal |title=New York-New Jersey Rail Project Gets Some Money in Congress Deal |date=March 21, 2018 |last1=Niquette |first1=Mark |last2=Wasson |first2=Erik |work=Bloomberg.com |access-date=March 28, 2018 |language=en |archive-date=April 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402161330/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/new-york-new-jersey-rail-project-said-to-get-some-money-in-deal |url-status=live }}</ref> which Democrats said could provide as much as $541 million for Gateway,<ref name="WAPO-Stuffing">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/03/22/heres-what-congress-is-stuffing-into-its-1-3-trillion-spending-bill/ |title=Here's what Congress is stuffing into its $1.3 trillion spending bill |last1=DeBonis |first1=Mike |date=March 22, 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=March 25, 2018 |last2=O'Keefe |first2=Ed |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286 |last3=Werner |first3=Erica |archive-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310021521/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/03/22/heres-what-congress-is-stuffing-into-its-1-3-trillion-spending-bill/ |url-status=live }}</ref> with $388 million coming from $650 million for improvements to the Northeast Corridor and another $153 million coming from FTA grants.<ref name="Bloomberg.com"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/a-pair-of-crucial-new-hudson-river-tunnels-just-took-a-major-step-forward-032718 |title=A pair of crucial new Hudson River tunnels just took a major step forward |last=Guse |first=Clayton |date=March 27, 2018 |work=Time Out New York |access-date=March 28, 2018 |language=en |archive-date=March 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328102710/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/a-pair-of-crucial-new-hudson-river-tunnels-just-took-a-major-step-forward-032718 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In June 2018, the State of New Jersey approved $600 million in bonds to finance the Portal Bridge part of the project.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tate |first=Curtis |date=June 15, 2018 |url=https://eu.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2018/06/15/portal-bridge-new-nj-state-funding-move-feds-chip/706246002/ |title=Will new state funding move the feds to chip in for Portal Bridge? |work=North Jersey |access-date=August 13, 2018 |language=en |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143536/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2018/06/15/portal-bridge-new-nj-state-funding-move-feds-chip/706246002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hutter |first=David |date=June 13, 2018 |url=http://www.njbiz.com/article/20180613/NJBIZ01/180619921/nj-transit-board-approves-600m-bond-to-replace-portal-bridge |title=NJ Transit board approves $600M bond to replace Portal Bridge |work=NJBIZ |access-date=August 13, 2018 |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824013308/http://www.njbiz.com/article/20180613/NJBIZ01/180619921/nj-transit-board-approves-600m-bond-to-replace-portal-bridge |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/18/06/12/floating-a-600-million-bond-issue-to-build-new-portal-bridge/ |title=Floating a $600 Million Bond Issue to Build New Portal Bridge |website=www.njspotlight.com |date=June 13, 2018 |last=Reitmeyer |first=John |access-date=August 13, 2018 |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619221748/http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/18/06/12/floating-a-600-million-bond-issue-to-build-new-portal-bridge/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In its 2020 budget, the Trump administration again proposed cutting funding for the Gateway Program by half, from $650 to $325 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/03/12/gateway-project-hudson-river-tunnel-north-river-tunnel-new-york-new-jersey/ |title=N.Y., N.J. Lawmakers Scramble For Backup Plan After Trump 2020 Budget Cuts Money From Gateway Project Fund |date=March 12, 2019 |work=CBS New York |access-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624223236/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/03/12/gateway-project-hudson-river-tunnel-north-river-tunnel-new-york-new-jersey/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Trump administration deals another blow to Gateway Tunnel |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/2020/03/trump-administration-deals-another-blow-to-gateway-tunnel.html |last1=Higgs |first1=Larry |last2=Salant |first2=Jonathan D. |date=March 5, 2020 |website=nj |language=en |access-date=May 5, 2020 |archive-date=May 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502025532/https://www.nj.com/politics/2020/03/trump-administration-deals-another-blow-to-gateway-tunnel.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=February 27, 2020 |title=More Pain for N.J. Commuters: Tunnel Repairs Could Cause Big Delays |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/27/nyregion/hudson-river-tunnel-repair.html |access-date=May 5, 2020 |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304111728/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/27/nyregion/hudson-river-tunnel-repair.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Creation of commission===

By 2019, project stakeholders had decided to create a bi-state agency to oversee the project's planning, funding, and construction of the rail tunnels and bridges. Creating the Gateway Development Commission required identical legislation in the New York and New Jersey legislatures, which both states passed on June 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Munoz |first=Daniel J. |title=Gateway project hits hurdle with NJ, NY calls for oversight |website=NJBIZ |date=April 22, 2019 |url=https://njbiz.com/gateway-project-hits-hurdle-nj-ny-calls-oversight/ |access-date=April 1, 2019 |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422222052/https://njbiz.com/gateway-project-hits-hurdle-nj-ny-calls-oversight/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Vielkind |first1=Jimmy |last2=Berger |first2=Paul |title=Gateway Rail Tunnel Project Hits Another Hurdle |website=WSJ |date=April 19, 2019 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/gateway-rail-tunnel-project-hits-another-hurdle-11555633942 |access-date=April 1, 2019 |archive-date=April 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419034017/https://www.wsj.com/articles/gateway-rail-tunnel-project-hits-another-hurdle-11555633942 |url-status=live }}</ref> The law set standards for transparency and accountability and said that each state was responsible for half the funding. The Commission could receive funds from federal, state, and local sources.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/infrastructure/article/21085913/bistate-legislation-passed-to-establish-gateway-development-commission |title=Bi-state legislation passed to establish Gateway Development Commission |last=Wanek-Libman |first=Mischa |date=June 24, 2019 |work=Mass Transit Magazine |access-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624220559/https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/infrastructure/article/21085913/bistate-legislation-passed-to-establish-gateway-development-commission |url-status=live }}</ref> The Commission's first CEO, Kris Kolluri, was nominated by New York governor [[Kathy Hochul]] and New Jersey governor [[Phil Murphy]] in early 2022.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fazelpoor |first=Matthew |title=Kolluri tapped to run Gateway Development Commission |website=NJBIZ |date=May 6, 2022 |url=https://njbiz.com/kolluri-tapped-to-run-gateway-development-commission/ |access-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-date=July 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705051152/https://njbiz.com/kolluri-tapped-to-run-gateway-development-commission/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hoogensen |first=Finn |title=Hochul, Murphy nominate CEO for Gateway Development Commission |website=PIX11 |date=May 7, 2022 |url=https://pix11.com/news/local-news/hochul-murphy-nominate-ceo-for-gateway-development-commission/ |access-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-date=May 14, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220514050033/https://pix11.com/news/local-news/hochul-murphy-nominate-ceo-for-gateway-development-commission/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Approval, funding, and start of construction under Biden===
With the inauguration of [[Joe Biden]] as U.S. President in January 2021, discussion resumed on funding the Gateway Program. Schumer, who had become [[Senate majority leader]], said that month he was working with Transportation Secretary [[Pete Buttigieg]]'s support to allocate $12 billion to the project.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hickman |first=Matt |date=January 26, 2021 |title=Stalled by Trump, $12 billion Gateway tunnel project poised to receive funding under Biden |url=https://www.archpaper.com/2021/01/stalled-by-trump-12-billion-gateway-tunnel-project-poised-to-receive-funding-under-biden/ |access-date=March 29, 2021 |website=The Architect's Newspaper |language=en-US |archive-date=January 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126211118/https://www.archpaper.com/2021/01/stalled-by-trump-12-billion-gateway-tunnel-project-poised-to-receive-funding-under-biden/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kaske |first=Michelle |date=January 25, 2021 |title=NYC's Hudson Rail Tunnel Likely to Get More Funds, Schumer Says |url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/nyc-s-hudson-rail-tunnel-likely-to-get-more-funds-schumer-says-1.1553717 |access-date=March 29, 2021 |website=BNN Bloomberg |archive-date=February 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210203023302/https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/nyc-s-hudson-rail-tunnel-likely-to-get-more-funds-schumer-says-1.1553717 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=March 26, 2021 |title=NYC-NJ tunnel plan has 'sense of urgency,' Buttigieg says |url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/nyc-nj-tunnel-plan-has-sense-urgency-buttigieg-says |access-date=March 29, 2021 |website=Crain's New York Business |agency=Bloomberg |language=en |archive-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330224254/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/nyc-nj-tunnel-plan-has-sense-urgency-buttigieg-says |url-status=live }}</ref>

On May 28, 2021, the project was formally approved by the federal government.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=May 28, 2021 |title=At Long Last, a New Rail Tunnel Under the Hudson River Can Be Built |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/28/nyregion/-gateway-tunnel-biden-support.html |access-date=May 28, 2021 |archive-date=May 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528152357/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/28/nyregion/-gateway-tunnel-biden-support.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Higgs 2021">{{cite web |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=May 28, 2021 |title=Gateway project to build new Hudson River tunnels wins key federal approval |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2021/05/gateway-project-to-build-new-hudson-river-tunnels-wins-key-federal-approval.html |access-date=May 28, 2021 |website=nj |archive-date=May 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528120917/https://www.nj.com/news/2021/05/gateway-project-to-build-new-hudson-river-tunnels-wins-key-federal-approval.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Porter 2021">{{cite web |last=Porter |first=David |date=May 28, 2021 |title=$11 Billion New York-New Jersey Rail Tunnel Gets Key Federal Approval |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/11-billion-new-york-new-jersey-rail-tunnel-gets-key-federal-approval/3080108/ |access-date=May 28, 2021 |website=NBC New York |archive-date=May 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528165934/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/11-billion-new-york-new-jersey-rail-tunnel-gets-key-federal-approval/3080108/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]], passed in November 2021, appropriated billions for projects like Gateway and other upgrades to the Northeast Corridor.<ref>{{cite news |title=Infrastructure bill includes billions for Northeast Corridor |first=T.A. |last=DeFeo |work=The Center Square |date=November 8, 2021 |access-date=November 13, 2021 |url=https://www.thecentersquare.com/new_jersey/infrastructure-bill-includes-billions-for-northeast-corridor/article_9e5e17f8-40ab-11ec-828d-17687f531bbe.html |archive-date=November 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211113223702/https://www.thecentersquare.com/new_jersey/infrastructure-bill-includes-billions-for-northeast-corridor/article_9e5e17f8-40ab-11ec-828d-17687f531bbe.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The next month, the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] gave final approval.<ref name="Katzban Group 2021">{{cite web |last=Katzban |first=Nicholas |title=Gateway Project clears final hurdle, but tunnel construction won't begin until 2023 |website=NorthJersey.com |date=December 1, 2021 |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2021/12/01/gateway-tunnel-project-clears-final-hurdle-digging-begins-2023/8826549002/ |access-date=December 2, 2021 |archive-date=January 22, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122185512/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2021/12/01/gateway-tunnel-project-clears-final-hurdle-digging-begins-2023/8826549002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Higgs 2021b">{{cite web |last=Higgs |first=Larry |title=Hudson River rail tunnel gets green light from the feds to start building it |website=nj |date=December 1, 2021 |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2021/12/hudson-river-rail-tunnel-gets-green-light-from-the-feds-to-start-building-it.html |access-date=December 2, 2021 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143537/https://www.nj.com/news/2021/12/hudson-river-rail-tunnel-gets-green-light-from-the-feds-to-start-building-it.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Early in 2022, the [[Federal Transit Administration]] upgraded the rating for the sought Federal Grant share of the tunnel to project, making it eligible for funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=NYC Gateway Tunnel Gets Set for Federal Funding as U.S. Raises Priority |first=Skylar |last=Woodhouse |website=Bloomberg |date=January 20, 2022 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-20/nyc-gateway-tunnel-to-receive-federal-funding-with-ratings-boost |access-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143536/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-20/nyc-gateway-tunnel-to-receive-federal-funding-with-ratings-boost |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2022, New Jersey and New York officials each agreed to pay 25 per cent of the project's cost; under the agreement, federal officials would pay 50 per cent.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=July 5, 2022 |title=Hudson River Tunnel Project Moves Ahead as States Agree to Share Costs |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/05/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-hudson-river.html |access-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-date=July 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705235025/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/05/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-hudson-river.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Katzban |first=Nicholas |title=NY and NJ governors sign memorandum to split cost of Gateway tunnel project |website=NorthJersey.com |date=July 6, 2022 |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2022/07/06/gateway-tunnel-project-ny-nj-split-cost-portal-bridge/65367635007/ |access-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-date=July 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706171545/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2022/07/06/gateway-tunnel-project-ny-nj-split-cost-portal-bridge/65367635007/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Higgs 202207">{{cite web | last=Higgs | first=Larry | title=N.J., N.Y. sign funding agreement on Gateway rail tunnel, bridge. Tunnel work could begin in 2023. | website=nj | date=July 5, 2022 | url=https://www.nj.com/news/2022/07/nj-ny-sign-funding-agreement-on-gateway-rail-tunnel-bridge-tunnel-work-could-begin-in-2023.html | access-date=December 30, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Westbrook 2022">{{cite web | last=Westbrook | first=Elijah | title=Governors Kathy Hochul and Phil Murphy sign $14B funding agreement for Gateway Hudson Tunnel project | website=CBS News | date=July 6, 2022 | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/gateway-hudson-tunnel-project-funding-agreement/ | access-date=December 30, 2022 | archive-date=December 30, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230002950/https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/gateway-hudson-tunnel-project-funding-agreement/ | url-status=live }}</ref> On August 31, 2022, the Gateway Development Commission announced the new tunnels would be completed in 2035 at a total cost of $16.1 billion.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |last=Rubinstein |first=Dana |date=August 31, 2022 |title=Commuter Tunnel Under the Hudson Won't Be Finished Until 2035 |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/31/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-ny-nj-delay.html |access-date=October 6, 2022 |archive-date=October 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006222107/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/31/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-ny-nj-delay.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Stoltz |first=Marsha A. |title=Hudson tunnel project will be delayed by three years and cost $2B more, commission says |website=NorthJersey.com |date=September 2, 2022 |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2022/09/02/hudson-tunnel-project-gateway-delayed-cost/65469949007/ |access-date=October 6, 2022 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143538/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2022/09/02/hudson-tunnel-project-gateway-delayed-cost/65469949007/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Crain's New York Business 2022">{{cite web |date=September 1, 2022 |title=Gateway tunnel cost jumps to $16.1B and construction start pushed back |url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/gateway-tunnel-cost-jumps-16-1b-and-construction-start-pushed-2024 |access-date=October 7, 2022 |website=Crain's New York Business |agency=Bloomberg |archive-date=October 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221007003251/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/gateway-tunnel-cost-jumps-16-1b-and-construction-start-pushed-2024 |url-status=live }}</ref> Schumer said in December 2022 that construction would commence in 2023 with $292 million in federal funding,<ref name="Sanderson 2022">{{cite web | last=Sanderson | first=Bill | title=Hudson River rail tunnel construction in NYC starting in 2023 with $292M federal grant, Schumer says | website=New York Daily News | date=December 29, 2022 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-gateway-tunnel-hudson-river-amtrak-schumer-penn-station-20221229-lmtcmzljdjatfehhehlxwyh2vi-story.html | access-date=December 30, 2022 | archive-date=December 30, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230002949/https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-gateway-tunnel-hudson-river-amtrak-schumer-penn-station-20221229-lmtcmzljdjatfehhehlxwyh2vi-story.html | url-status=live }}</ref> which Biden announced would be used to complete the [[#Hudson Yards "tunnel box" and West Side Yard|Hudson Yards "tunnel box"]].<ref name="Tillman 202301">{{cite web | last=Tillman | first=Rachel | title=Biden announces 9 'mega' grants for infrastructure projects | website=Spectrum News NY1 New York City | date=January 30, 2023 | url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2023/01/30/biden-to-announce--292-million-for-hudson-rail-tunnel-project-during-nyc-visit | access-date=February 1, 2023 | archive-date=February 1, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230201000418/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2023/01/30/biden-to-announce--292-million-for-hudson-rail-tunnel-project-during-nyc-visit | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Brachfeld 202301">{{cite web | last=Brachfeld | first=Ben | title='We're going to get it done': Biden touts $300M investment in Gateway Tunnel project on visit to NYC | website=amNewYork | date=January 31, 2023 | url=https://www.amny.com/transit/biden-touts-gateway-tunnel-project-nyc/ | access-date=February 1, 2023 | archive-date=February 1, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230201000417/https://www.amny.com/transit/biden-touts-gateway-tunnel-project-nyc/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2023, the FTA promised a $6.88 billion grant, the largest transit grant that the federal government had ever given,<ref name="The New York Times 2023 h121">{{cite news |first=Patrick |last=McGeehan |title=Hudson Tunnel Project to Get $6.9 Billion in Largest U.S. Transit Grant |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |date=July 6, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/06/nyregion/nyc-penn-station-tunnel-gateway.html |access-date=August 24, 2023 |archive-date=August 23, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230823154445/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/06/nyregion/nyc-penn-station-tunnel-gateway.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Brachfeld 2023 v346">{{cite web | last=Brachfeld | first=Ben | title=Biden admin awards nearly $7B to Gateway Tunnel project, largest federal transit grant in US history | website=amNewYork | date=July 6, 2023 | url=https://www.amny.com/transit/gateway-tunnel-project-federal-funding/ | access-date=August 24, 2023}}</ref> and the grant was handed to the Gateway Development Corporation in July 2024.<ref>{{cite web | last=Bergeron | first=Tom | title=Time to dig: Gateway Tunnel project gets full-funding grant ($6.8B) from federal government | website=ROI-NJ | date=June 12, 2024 | url=https://www.roi-nj.com/2024/06/12/politics/time-to-dig-gateway-tunnel-project-gets-full-funding-grant-6-8-billion-from-federal-government/ | access-date=June 12, 2024 | archive-date=June 12, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240612145527/https://www.roi-nj.com/2024/06/12/politics/time-to-dig-gateway-tunnel-project-gets-full-funding-grant-6-8-billion-from-federal-government/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=McGeehan | first=Patrick | title=Gateway Tunnel Project Under Hudson River Gets Final Green Light | website=The New York Times | date=June 11, 2024 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/06/11/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-amtrak-funding.html | access-date=June 12, 2024 | archive-date=June 12, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240612010839/https://www.nytimes.com/2024/06/11/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-amtrak-funding.html | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Siff | first=Andrew | title=$16 billion Gateway Tunnel Project gets federal funding boost after years of delays | website=NBC New York | date=July 8, 2024 | url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/traffic/transit-traffic/gateway-tunnel-project-federal-funding-construction-underway-delays/5576135/ | access-date=July 9, 2024 | archive-date=July 9, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240709001611/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/traffic/transit-traffic/gateway-tunnel-project-federal-funding-construction-underway-delays/5576135/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Gateway rail tunnel project: Officials announce $6.8B grant to fund long-delayed path between NYC, NJ | website=ABC7 New York | date=July 8, 2024 | url=https://abc7ny.com/post/gateway-rail-tunnel-project-officials-announce-68b-grant/15042403/ | access-date=July 9, 2024 | archive-date=July 8, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240708235958/https://abc7ny.com/post/gateway-rail-tunnel-project-officials-announce-68b-grant/15042403/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Another $3.8 billion grant was provided in November 2023;<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|last=McGeehan|first=Patrick|date=November 3, 2023|title=New Phase of Gateway Tunnel Project in Hudson River to Begin|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/03/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-amtrak-hudson-river.html|access-date=November 7, 2023|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Wilson 2023 v852">{{cite web | last=Wilson | first=Colleen | title=NJ share of Gateway tunnel project cost to drop, feds add $4B | website=Bergen Record | date=November 3, 2023 | url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2023/11/03/nj-share-gateway-tunnel-project-cost-drop-federal-funding/71438151007/ | access-date=November 7, 2023 | archive-date=November 7, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231107034355/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2023/11/03/nj-share-gateway-tunnel-project-cost-drop-federal-funding/71438151007/ | url-status=live }}</ref> in total, $12 billion in federal funding for the $16 billion project was committed by the [[2024 United States presidential election|2024 presidential election]], bringing the project to a "point of no return".<ref>{{cite web | title=Hudson Tunnel Project Awaits Final Approval in NYC | website=Hudson Reporter | last=Lookman | first=Moses | date=May 30, 2024 | url=https://hudsonreporter.com/news/north-bergen/hudson-tunnel-project/ | access-date=June 3, 2024 | archive-date=June 3, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240603131253/https://hudsonreporter.com/news/north-bergen/hudson-tunnel-project/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Woodhouse |first=Skylar |date=May 14, 2024 |title=NYC Rail Project Heads for 'Point of No Return' Before Election |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-14/nyc-rail-project-heads-for-point-of-no-return-before-election |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240514205255/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-14/nyc-rail-project-heads-for-point-of-no-return-before-election |archive-date=May 14, 2024 |access-date=November 14, 2024 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref>

Construction began in 2023 with various pieces underway as of 2025. The Tonnelle Avenue overpass was expected to be completed in October 2025, concrete casing near Hudson Yards is expected in 2026, Hudson River ground stabilization is projected by March 2027, the Palisades tunnel approach on the New Jersey side is expected to be completed in 2027, and the Manhattan tunnel project will clear a path on the New York side by October 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wilson |first=Colleen |date=2025-04-14 |title=A new tunnel will soon connect New York and New Jersey |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2025/04/14/first-phase-of-nj-entrance-to-gateway-rail-tunnel-nearly-finished/83080509007/ |access-date=2025-05-29 |website=northjersey.com |language=en-US |archive-date=May 30, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250530015753/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2025/04/14/first-phase-of-nj-entrance-to-gateway-rail-tunnel-nearly-finished/83080509007/ |url-status=live }}</ref> At the time, the tunnel is scheduled to open in 2035, with the rehabilitation of the existing North River Tunnels to be completed by 2038.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rahmanan |first=Anna |date=2024-07-11 |title=A new tunnel will soon connect New York and New Jersey |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/a-new-tunnel-will-soon-connect-new-york-and-new-jersey-071124 |access-date=2024-07-12 |website=Time Out New York |language=en-US |archive-date=July 12, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240712193007/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/a-new-tunnel-will-soon-connect-new-york-and-new-jersey-071124 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Advocacy controversy ===
In August 2025, the editorial board of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' reported that the [[Regional Plan Association]] received support from [[Amtrak]] to operate the Build Gateway Now coalition and contended that this compromised the group's independence in debates over Penn Station and the Gateway Program.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Long-trusted nonprofit sells its independence to Amtrak, casting doubt on Penn Station views |work=New York Daily News |issn=2692-1251 |date=August 24, 2025 |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/2025/08/24/rpa-sells-out-to-amtrak-taking-railroads-money-to-promote-gateway-boondoggle-compromises-its-independence/ |access-date=August 25, 2025 |archive-date=August 24, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250824173114/https://www.nydailynews.com/2025/08/24/rpa-sells-out-to-amtrak-taking-railroads-money-to-promote-gateway-boondoggle-compromises-its-independence/ |url-status=live }}</ref> RPA's fiscal year 2023 Form 990 discloses that this coalition work was supported by Amtrak, noting a grant of $350,000 for 18 months beginning in January 2022 and a renewed grant of $500,000 for 18 months beginning in January 2024, and it describes activities that include research, communications, and advocacy such as testifying at Gateway Development Commission board meetings.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax, FY2023 Form 990 |publisher=Regional Plan Association |date=February 6, 2024 |url=https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/rpa-org/pdfs/FY2023-Form-990.pdf |access-date=August 25, 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=The Gateway Program |publisher=Regional Plan Association |url=https://rpa.org/work/campaigns/build-gateway |access-date=August 25, 2025}}</ref> Amtrak documentation identifies RPA president Tom Wright as a co-chair of the Penn Station Working Advisory Group convened in 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Penn Station Working Advisory Group Meeting Summary |publisher=Amtrak |date=September 17, 2024 |url=https://www.amtrak.com/content/dam/projects/dotcom/english/public/documents/ny-penn-station-working-advisory-group/penn-working-advisory-group-meeting-summary-091724.pdf |access-date=August 25, 2025}}</ref>

=== Second Trump administration ===
In June 2025, the second Trump administration proposed to allocate a combined $1 billion for the project and [[Second Avenue Subway Phase 2]],<ref name="Rivard y405">{{cite web|last1=Rivard|first1=Ry|last2=Sentner|first2=Irie|last3=Ngo|first3=Emily|last4=Marquette|first4=Chris|last5=Fuchs|first5=Hailey|last6=Wu|first6=Nicholas|date=2025-10-01|title=Trump to withhold billions of dollars from Gateway tunnel and Second Ave. subway projects|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/10/01/trump-to-withhold-billions-of-dollars-from-gateway-tunnel-and-second-ave-subway-projects-00589772|access-date=2025-10-01|website=POLITICO|archive-date=October 1, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251001193321/https://www.politico.com/news/2025/10/01/trump-to-withhold-billions-of-dollars-from-gateway-tunnel-and-second-ave-subway-projects-00589772|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Spivack|first=Caroline|date=2025-06-11|title=Trump admin proposes $1B for city transportation projects|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/trump-admin-proposes-1b-new-york-city-transportation-projects|access-date=2025-10-01|website=Crain&#039;s New York Business|archive-date=October 16, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251016031743/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/trump-admin-proposes-1b-new-york-city-transportation-projects|url-status=live}}</ref> but in October, at the start of the [[2025 United States federal government shutdown]], [[Office of Management and Budget]] director [[Russell Vought]] withheld a combined $18 billion for the two projects, citing reports of [[diversity, equity, and inclusion]] (DEI) practices that he described as "unconstitutional".<ref>{{cite web |last=Haag|first=Matthew|date=2025-10-01|title=Trump Administration to Withhold $18 Billion for N.Y.C. Infrastructure|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/10/01/nyregion/trump-nyc-subway-gateway-infrastructure-funding.html|access-date=2025-10-01|website=The New York Times|postscript=none}}; {{cite web |last1=Kaske|first1=Michelle|last2=Taylor|first2=Sri|last3=Nahmias|first3=Laura|last4=Korte|first4=Gregory|date=2025-10-01|title=US Halts $18 Billion NYC Infrastructure Funds as Shutdown Hits|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-10-01/us-halts-18-billion-of-nyc-infrastructure-funds-on-dei-concerns|access-date=2025-10-01|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref> ''[[Politico]]'' reported that Vought was retaliating for the government shutdown,<ref name="Rivard y405" /> and Trump later vowed to terminate the funding entirely.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hernandez|first=Laura Figueroa|title=Trump says Gateway tunnel project funding, already suspended, is 'terminated'|website=Newsday|date=October 16, 2025|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/gateway-trump-schumer-funding-qnbs842i|access-date=October 16, 2025|postscript=none}}; {{cite web |last=Haag|first=Matthew|title=Trump Says $16 Billion Hudson River Tunnel Project Is ‘Terminated’|website=The New York Times|date=October 15, 2025|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/10/15/nyregion/trump-gateway-cancellation.html|access-date=October 16, 2025}}</ref> Work continued for several months, after the Gateway Development Commission obtained a [[line of credit]].<ref name="Martinez b692">{{cite web | last=Martinez | first=Jose | title=Key Rail Tunnel Under Hudson Could Derail By Next Week Without Federal Funds | website=THE CITY - NYC News | date=January 27, 2026 | url=https://www.thecity.nyc/2026/01/27/gateway-amtrak-trump-funding-nj-transit/ | access-date=January 30, 2026 | archive-date=January 30, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260130012636/https://www.thecity.nyc/2026/01/27/gateway-amtrak-trump-funding-nj-transit/ | url-status=live }}</ref> By late 2025, pieces of the two [[tunnel boring machine]]s (TBMs) were being shipped to New Jersey for assembly.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaske |first=Michelle |date=2025-12-15 |title=Hudson Tunnel Digging Work to Start as Boring Machines Ready |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-12-15/hudson-tunnel-s-digging-work-to-start-as-boring-machines-arrive |access-date=2025-12-17 |website=Bloomberg.com |postscript=none |archive-date=March 1, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260301163212/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-12-15/hudson-tunnel-s-digging-work-to-start-as-boring-machines-arrive |url-status=live }}; {{cite web | last=Fazelpoor | first=Matthew | title=Hudson Tunnel Project clears TBM milestone, nears tunneling | website=NJBIZ | date=2025-12-17 | url=https://njbiz.com/hudson-tunnel-project-tbm-milestone-testing/ | access-date=2025-12-17 | archive-date=December 17, 2025 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251217142521/https://njbiz.com/hudson-tunnel-project-tbm-milestone-testing/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In December, when work on the Tonnelle Avenue overpass was nearly complete<ref>{{cite web |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=2025-12-16 |title=First Gateway Tunnel Project almost done, despite 2-month federal payment freeze |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2025/12/first-gateway-tunnel-project-almost-done-despite-2-month-federal-payment-freeze.html |access-date=2025-12-17 |website=nj |archive-date=December 18, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251218025130/https://www.nj.com/news/2025/12/first-gateway-tunnel-project-almost-done-despite-2-month-federal-payment-freeze.html |url-status=live }}</ref>,  administration officials said the funding for the projects could be unfrozen if they discontinued DEI practices.<ref>{{cite web | last=Simko-Bednarski | first=Evan | title=Scrap DEI to restore Second Ave. subway, Hudson Tunnel projects' funding: feds | website=New York Daily News | date=December 2, 2025 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/2025/12/02/feds-tell-mta-gateway-get-into-compliance-funding-restoration/ | access-date=December 4, 2025}}</ref> 

Officials announced in January 2026 that work would stop on February 6 unless the administration lifted its funding freeze.<ref>{{cite web | last=Rivard | first=Ry | title=Work on Gateway tunnel project linking New York and New Jersey to pause next month without federal dollars | website=POLITICO | date=January 27, 2026 | url=https://www.politico.com/news/2026/01/27/work-on-gateway-to-pause-next-month-without-federal-dollars-00748393 | access-date=January 28, 2026 | postscript=none }}; {{cite web | last=McGeehan | first=Patrick | title=Work Will Stop on Tunnel Project Between NY and NJ Unless Trump Restores Funding | website=The New York Times | date=January 27, 2026 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/27/nyregion/hudson-tunnel-gateway-funding.html | access-date=January 28, 2026 | archive-date=January 27, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260127180939/https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/27/nyregion/hudson-tunnel-gateway-funding.html | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Nessen z594"/> Schumer asked federal officials to unfreeze $4.38 billion that had been approved under Biden's tenure.<ref>{{cite web | last=Stark-Miller | first=Ethan | title=Dire consequences loom for NYC area if Trump allows Gateway Tunnel rail project to stall without funding, Schumer warns – amNewYork | website=amNewYork | date=January 27, 2026 | url=https://www.amny.com/news/trump-gateway-tunnel-project-funding-schumer/ | access-date=January 28, 2026 | archive-date=January 27, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260127221450/https://www.amny.com/news/trump-gateway-tunnel-project-funding-schumer/ | url-status=live }}</ref> One administration spokesperson said the freeze had not been lifted because of Democratic politicians' opposition to [[Immigration policy of the second Trump administration|Trump's immigration policy]]<ref name="Martinez b692"/><ref name="Nessen z594">{{cite web | last=Nessen | first=Stephen | title=Trump's cuts may halt work on $16B Hudson River train tunnel project, officials say | website=Gothamist | date=January 27, 2026 | url=https://gothamist.com/news/trumps-cuts-may-halt-work-on-16b-hudson-river-train-tunnel-project-officials-say | access-date=January 30, 2026 | archive-date=January 30, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260130021010/https://gothamist.com/news/trumps-cuts-may-halt-work-on-16b-hudson-river-train-tunnel-project-officials-say | url-status=live }}</ref>. Trump himself said he would release the funds if [[Dulles Airport]] and [[New York Penn Station]] were renamed for him.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stein |first=Chris |date=2026-02-06 |title=Trump says he’ll free infrastructure funds for New York if Penn Station is renamed after him |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/feb/06/trump-penn-station-dulles-airport-renaming |access-date=2026-02-07 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |postscript=none }}; {{cite web | last1=Raju | first1=Manu | last2=Cancryn | first2=Adam | title=if Penn Station and Dulles Airport are renamed after him | website=CNN | date=February 5, 2026 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2026/02/05/politics/schumer-trump-ny-funding-rename | access-date=February 7, 2026 | postscript=none | archive-date=February 7, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260207044727/https://www.cnn.com/2026/02/05/politics/schumer-trump-ny-funding-rename | url-status=live }}; {{cite web | last1=Nobles | first1=Ryan | last2=Haake | first2=Garrett | last3=Uribe | first3=Raquel Coronell | title=Trump wanted Dulles Airport, Penn Station named after him | website=NBC News | date=February 6, 2026 | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-asked-dulles-penn-station-named-exchange-gateway-money-released-rcna257708 | access-date=February 7, 2026 | archive-date=February 6, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260206231123/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-asked-dulles-penn-station-named-exchange-gateway-money-released-rcna257708 | url-status=live }}</ref> In early February, the Gateway Development Commission sued to unfreeze the funding,<ref>{{cite web | last=McGeehan | first=Patrick | title=Trump Administration Sued Over Cutting Off Funds for $16 Billion Tunnel | website=The New York Times | date=2026-02-03 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/02/02/nyregion/hudson-river-tunnel-lawsuit-gateway.html | access-date=2026-02-03 | postscript=none | archive-date=February 3, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260203220110/https://www.nytimes.com/2026/02/02/nyregion/hudson-river-tunnel-lawsuit-gateway.html | url-status=live }}; {{cite web | last=Martinez | first=Jose | title=Gateway Megaproject Sues Feds for Withheld Funds Ahead of Looming Work Shutdown | website=THE CITY - NYC News | date=2026-02-03 | url=https://www.thecity.nyc/2026/02/03/gateway-funding-lawsuit-river-tunnel-work/ | access-date=2026-02-03 | archive-date=February 3, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260203192345/https://www.thecity.nyc/2026/02/03/gateway-funding-lawsuit-river-tunnel-work/ | url-status=live }}</ref> and the New Jersey and New York state governments filed a similar lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web | last=Smith | first=Christen | title=New York, New Jersey sue feds over Hudson Tunnel funding cuts | website=Mountain Democrat | date=2026-01-20 | url=https://www.mtdemocrat.com/news/national/new-york-new-jersey-sue-feds-over-hudson-tunnel-funding-cuts/article_a33fadfc-6814-5854-a287-b0c052d10422.html | access-date=2026-02-04 | postscript=none }}{{Dead link|date=May 2026 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}; {{cite web | last=Westbrook | first=Elijah | title=N.Y., N.J. sue Trump administration over Gateway Tunnel funds, which are set to run out Friday | website=CBS New York | date=2026-02-04 | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/ny-nj-gateway-tunnel-project-lawsuit/ | access-date=2026-02-04 | archive-date=February 5, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260205101748/https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/ny-nj-gateway-tunnel-project-lawsuit/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Construction was suspended on February 5,<ref>{{cite web | title=Gateway Project on verge of indefinite shutdown after Trump pulls funding | website=CBS New York | date=February 5, 2026 | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/video/gateway-project-on-verge-of-indefinite-shutdown-after-trump-pulls-funding/ | access-date=February 6, 2026 | postscript=none | archive-date=February 7, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260207175047/https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/video/gateway-project-on-verge-of-indefinite-shutdown-after-trump-pulls-funding/ | url-status=live }}; {{cite web | last1=Gottlieb | first1=Bryan | last2=Rice | first2=Justin | title=UPDATE: Judge Orders Feds to Release Funds for Gateway Hudson River Tunnel, Hours After Officials Announce Project Suspension | website=Engineering News-Record | date=February 6, 2026 | url=https://www.enr.com/articles/62483-update-judge-orders-feds-to-release-funds-for-gateway-hudson-river-tunnel-hours-after-officials-announce-project-suspension | access-date=February 7, 2026 | archive-date=February 7, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260207133856/https://www.enr.com/articles/62483-update-judge-orders-feds-to-release-funds-for-gateway-hudson-river-tunnel-hours-after-officials-announce-project-suspension | url-status=live }}</ref> when $2 billion had been spent on the project.<ref name="Nessen q727">{{cite web | last=Nessen | first=Stephen | title=One of America's biggest construction jobs halts as Trump defunds Hudson River tunnels | website=Gothamist | date=February 5, 2026 | url=https://gothamist.com/news/one-of-americas-biggest-construction-jobs-halts-as-trump-defunds-hudson-river-tunnels | access-date=February 6, 2026 | archive-date=February 6, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260206003443/https://gothamist.com/news/one-of-americas-biggest-construction-jobs-halts-as-trump-defunds-hudson-river-tunnels | url-status=live }}</ref> A judge ruled the next day that the funds should be unfrozen,<ref>{{cite web | first=Jack |last=Queen | first2=David |last2=Shepardson | title=US judge unfreezes funding for $16 billion New York City tunnel project | website=Reuters | date=February 6, 2026 | url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/work-be-suspended-16-billion-new-york-city-tunnel-project-friday-2026-02-06/ | access-date=February 7, 2026|postscript=none}}; {{cite web | last1=McGeehan | first1=Patrick | last2=Cameron | first2=Chris | title=U.S. Judge Says Trump Cannot Halt Funding for Gateway Tunnel Project | website=The New York Times | date=February 6, 2026 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/02/06/nyregion/gateway-tunnel-project-funding-trump.html | access-date=February 7, 2026|postscript=none}}; {{Cite news |date=2026-02-07 |title=Federal judge reverses Trump’s freeze on $16bn for NY-NJ tunnel project |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/feb/07/federal-judge-reverses-trump-freeze-ny-nj-tunnel |access-date=2026-02-07 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and funding was released the following week.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Simko-Bednarski | first1=Evan | last2=Crane-Newman | first2=Molly | title=$30 million in fed funds temporarily ends tunnel freeze | website=New York Daily News | date=February 13, 2026 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/2026/02/13/feds-send-30-million-to-gateway-for-hudson-river-tunnel-temporarily-ending-funding-freeze/ | access-date=February 14, 2026 | postscript=none | archive-date=February 14, 2026 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260214043533/https://www.nydailynews.com/2026/02/13/feds-send-30-million-to-gateway-for-hudson-river-tunnel-temporarily-ending-funding-freeze/ | url-status=live }}; {{cite web | title=Gateway Tunnel project goes to court: Judge says Trump administration in compliance with court order on funding | website=ABC7 New York | date=February 13, 2026 | url=https://abc7ny.com/post/federal-court-order-blocking-205m-gateway-tunnel-project-expires-nj-ny-call-funds-released/18594924/ | access-date=February 14, 2026 }}</ref> Work resumed in late February.<ref>{{cite web | last=Stark-Miller | first=Ethan | title=Gateway Tunnel: Construction on new Hudson River rail tunnel set to restart Wednesday after feds released funds, commission says | website=amNewYork | date=February 24, 2026 | url=https://www.amny.com/nyc-transit/gateway-tunnel-construction-restart-02242026/ | access-date=February 27, 2026}}</ref>

