== Project components ==
The current route, about {{convert|11|mi|km}} long, includes infrastructure that was built in the 1900s and 1910s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGeehan |first1=Patrick |last2=Glanz |first2=James |date=August 20, 2024 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/20/nyregion/amtrak-njtransit-delays.html |title=Why Amtrak's System Keeps Breaking Down: It's 100 Years Old |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 25, 2024 |archive-date=August 25, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240825054839/https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/20/nyregion/amtrak-njtransit-delays.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The system operates at capacity during peak hours—24 trains per hour—and limits speed for safety reasons.<ref name=TravelTrends-Aftermath-2006/> The new route would run parallel to the current right-of-way, enabling dispatching alternatives, potential speed increases, and up to 24 more trains per hour.<ref name=GPDC-Board-201701/>

===Newark Penn, Dock Bridge, and Harrison PATH station===
[[File:Harrisontrainjeh.jpg|thumb|NEC passes through Harrison Station.]]
Six tracks connect [[Newark Penn Station]] and the adjacent [[Dock Bridge]] over the [[Passaic River]] at {{coord|40|44|05|N|74|9|51|W|type:railwaystation_region:US-NJ|display=inline}}. The station and the west span of the bridge, carrying three tracks, were built in 1935. The east span, opened in 1937, carries one outbound track and the two [[Port Authority Trans Hudson]] (PATH) [[rapid transit]] tracks. To the northeast lies the PATH's [[Harrison station (PATH)|Harrison station]]. From the bridge and through the station, Amtrak and NJT trains run on three center tracks; the PATH uses [[side platform]]s. Maps for the Gateway Program indicate that a fourth track for the NEC will be added through the station.<ref name="GatewayPDF" />

The bridge, owned by the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] (PANYNJ), was repaired in 2009.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=May 28, 2009 |title=Rules and Regulation |url=http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/2009/pdf/E9-12383.pdf |url-status=live |journal=Federal Register |volume=74 |issue=101 |page=25448 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721041009/http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/2009/pdf/E9-12383.pdf |archive-date=July 21, 2011 |access-date=February 14, 2011}}</ref>

In the 2010s, the station received a $173 million reconstruction and expansion. Unrelated to the Gateway Program, it was funded by the PANYNJ, which owns and operates the PATH, and the [[Federal Transit Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Harrison PATH Station |work=Daily Harrison |url=http://www.dailyharrison.com/harrison-path-station |access-date=February 15, 2011 |archive-date=February 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224160752/http://www.dailyharrison.com/harrison-path-station |url-status=live }}</ref>

===<span class="anchor" id="Sawtooth Bridges"></span>Sawtooth Bridges-Kearny Meadows===
[[File:Avelia Liberty Kearny Junction.jpg|thumb|Amtrak Bridge 7.80 crossing over NJTransit]]

At  the [[Sawtooth Bridges]] at {{Coord|40|44|38|N|74|7|30|W}}<ref>{{cite web |title=NEC INFRASTRUCTURE PROJECTS OF RELEVANCE TO NEW JERSEY |publisher=ARP |date=January 2013 |url=http://www.nj-arp.org/Assets/nec%20infrastructure%20projects%20of%20relevance%20to%20nj.pdf |access-date=January 19, 2016 |archive-date=January 26, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126225904/http://www.nj-arp.org/Assets/nec%20infrastructure%20projects%20of%20relevance%20to%20nj.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> east of the former [[Manhattan Transfer (PRR station)|Manhattan Transfer]], the rights-of-way of Amtrak, and PATH, and several NJT lines converge and run parallel to each other. While there is no junction with PATH, NJT trains can switch tracks, depending on their terminal of origination or destination, enabling [[Midtown Direct]] trains on the [[Morris and Essex Lines]] to join or depart the [[Northeast Corridor]].<ref name="Allaboard" /><ref name="NJaddtrains" /> The single track limited-use [[Waterfront Connection]] connects some lines using diesel trains on [[Hoboken Terminal]] trips with the NEC to the west.<ref name="wtrfrntconnect" /> Plans call for replacement of the bridges and expansion from two to four tracks, requiring the construction of bridges in the [[Kearny Meadows]] at [[Newark Turnpike]] and [[Belleville Turnpike]].<ref name="GatewayPDF" />

=== Portal Bridge ===
{{main|Portal North Bridge}}

[[File:Portal.Bridge.NJ.jpg|thumb|250x250px|The Portal Bridge is a major pinch point of the Northeast Corridor, as problems closing the bridge cause delays for thousands of rail commuters.]]
[[File:Secaucus Junct CR 653 jeh.JPG|thumb|250px|The right-of-way would parallel the NEC and pass through Secaucus Junction]]

The ''Portal Bridge Replacement'' will replace the existing [[Portal Bridge]], built in 1910, with the [[Portal North Bridge]], which will replace the tracks on the existing Portal Bridge one-by-one, and yield reliability improvements, but not increase capacity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gateway Project advances, Portal North Bridge included |first=Daniel |last=Israel |date=May 21, 2021 |work=Hudson Reporter |url=https://hudsonreporter.com/2021/05/21/commitments-made-to-advance-gateway-project-including-portal-north-bridge/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210627132352/https://hudsonreporter.com/2021/05/21/commitments-made-to-advance-gateway-project-including-portal-north-bridge/ |archive-date=June 27, 2021}}</ref> A proposed Portal South Bridge, which is not  funded as of 2025,<ref name="GatewayPDF" /><ref>{{cite web |title=The Gateway Program |url=https://www.gatewayprogram.org/aboutgateway.html |access-date=2025-06-23 |publisher=Gateway Development Commission |location=New York, NY |archive-date=May 20, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250520193744/https://www.gatewayprogram.org/aboutgateway.html |url-status=live }}</ref> would double the number of tracks to four, thus matching the rest of the Northeast Corridor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Other Gateway Program Projects |date=August 9, 2022 |url=https://www.gatewayprogram.org/other-projects.html |publisher=Gateway Development Commission |access-date=29 November 2024 |ref=gateway commission - list other projects |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240720175641/https://www.gatewayprogram.org/other-projects.html |archive-date=July 20, 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

The old Portal Bridge is a two-track, rail-only, {{convert|961|ft|m|adj=on}} [[swing bridge]] over the [[Hackensack River]] between [[Kearny, New Jersey|Kearny]] and [[Secaucus, New Jersey|Secaucus]]. Its design limits train speeds, temporarily prohibits crossings when open, and requires frequent and costly maintenance.<ref name="approval" /><ref name = Fedsopen/> Its lowest beams are {{convert|23|ft|m}} above the water, so it opens regularly for shipping,<ref name="Fedsopen">{{cite web |last=Baldwin |first=Zoe |title=Feds Open "Portal" to Expansion of NJ Transit's Network |publisher=Mobilizing the Region |date=January 8, 2009 |url=http://blog.tstc.org/2009/01/08/feds-open-portal-to-expansion-of-nj-transits-network/ |access-date=February 10, 2011 |archive-date=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919144702/http://blog.tstc.org/2009/01/08/feds-open-portal-to-expansion-of-nj-transits-network/ |url-status=live }}</ref> though not during weekday rush hours, when trains have priority.<ref name="cfr33v1">{{Cite web |url=http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/cfr_2007/julqtr/33cfr117.723.htm |title=Code of Federal Regulations, Title 33, Volume 1 |date=July 1, 2007 |website=Code of Federal Regulations |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |pages=616–617 |access-date=September 11, 2012 |archive-date=July 21, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721040959/http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/cfr_2007/julqtr/33cfr117.723.htm |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition to the drawbacks that come with the swing bridge design itself, due to its substantial age and bad state of repair the Portal Bridge frequently failed to close properly after swinging back, causing major disruptions for riders on [[NJ Transit]] and Amtrak.<ref name="nyt old portal bridge">{{cite news |last1=McGeehan |first1=Patrick |title=For 80,000 Commuters, One Nemesis: A 108-Year-Old Bridge |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/nyregion/portal-bridge-amtrak-train-delays.html |access-date=29 November 2024 |work=New York Times |date=11 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125122000/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/nyregion/portal-bridge-amtrak-train-delays.html |archive-date=November 25, 2022 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2008, the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) approved a $1.34 billion project to replace the Portal Bridge with two new bridges: a three-track bridge to the north, and a two-track bridge to the south.<ref name="approval" /> Construction on the new bridges had originally been scheduled to begin in 2010 and complete in 2017, but the project encountered numerous delays and was reduced to a single two-track bridge primarily due to a lack of state and federal funding during the Republican administrations of New Jersey Governor, [[Chris Christie]] and U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], both of whom opposed the project.<ref name="NJAmtrak" /><ref name="GatewayPDF" /><ref name="Portal Bridge Capacity Enhancement" /><ref name="approval" /><ref name="Fleisher" /><ref>{{cite web |title=AECOM JV Bags US$18 Mln Contract For New Jersey's Portal Bridge Replacement Project – Quick Facts |url=http://www.rttnews.com/Content/QuickFacts.aspx?Node=B1&Id=1170705%20&Category=Quick%20Facts |date=January 5, 2010 |publisher=RTT News |access-date=January 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715211216/http://www.rttnews.com/Content/QuickFacts.aspx?Node=B1&Id=1170705%20&Category=Quick%20Facts |archive-date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref> In June 2020, Trump informed NJ Governor [[Phil Murphy]] that he would no longer oppose the Portal Bridge replacement, allowing the project to begin once it could be properly financed.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Racioppi |first=Dustin |date=June 20, 2020 |title=Portal Bridge clears major hurdle and likely to get funding for replacement, Murphy says |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2020/06/19/portal-bridge-replacement-clears-major-funding-hurdle-murphy-says/3226334001/ |access-date=June 27, 2021 |work=northjersey.com |publisher=North Jersey Media Group |language=en-US |archive-date=August 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210805190521/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2020/06/19/portal-bridge-replacement-clears-major-funding-hurdle-murphy-says/3226334001/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Construction on the Portal North bridge began on August 1, 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breaking ground for new Portal North Bridge in New Jersey |url=https://abc7ny.com/nj-portal-bridge-north-hackensack-river/12090335/ |work=[[WABC-TV]] |date=August 1, 2022 |access-date=August 6, 2022 |archive-date=August 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220809174515/https://abc7ny.com/nj-portal-bridge-north-hackensack-river/12090335/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first of the Portal North Bridge's three arches was floated into place in November 2024<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caloway |first1=Nick |title=Key milestone reached for new Portal North Bridge |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/portal-north-bridge-arch-arrives/ |access-date=29 November 2024 |work=CBS New York |date=26 November 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241127032257/https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/portal-north-bridge-arch-arrives/ |archive-date=November 27, 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>, and the last arch was floated into place in February 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bergeron |first=Tom |date=2025-02-20 |title=In major milestone for NJ Transit, final span for Portal North Bridge arrives |url=https://www.roi-nj.com/2025/02/20/politics/in-major-milestone-for-nj-transit-final-span-for-portal-north-bridge-arrives/ |access-date=2026-04-05 |website=ROI-NJ |language=en-US |archive-date=April 29, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260429135455/https://www.roi-nj.com/2025/02/20/politics/in-major-milestone-for-nj-transit-final-span-for-portal-north-bridge-arrives/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The first track on the bridge entered service on March 13, 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wilson |first=Colleen |title=In baptism by fire, here's how new Portal Bridge opened early |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2026/03/13/how-new-portal-bridge-opened-early-nj-transit-amtrak-new-jersey/89134365007/ |access-date=2026-04-05 |website=North Jersey Media Group |language=en-US |archive-date=March 16, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260316012334/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2026/03/13/how-new-portal-bridge-opened-early-nj-transit-amtrak-new-jersey/89134365007/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Secaucus Junction–Bergen Loop===

Opened on December 15, 2003, at a cost of $450 million, [[Secaucus Junction]] (at {{coord|40.76161|N|74.074985|W|type:railwaystation_region:US-NJ|display=inline}}) is an [[interchange station]] served by nine of New Jersey Transit's rail lines, and is sited where [[Hoboken Terminal]] trains intersect with those traveling along the [[Northeast Corridor]]. Passenger transfers are possible, but there is no [[rail junction]]. While Access to the Region's Core had planned a loop to create a junction,<ref name="ARC">{{Cite web |url=http://www.arctunnel.com/ |title=ARC Access to the Region's Core |publisher=New Jersey Transit |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=February 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202055734/http://www.arctunnel.com/ |url-status=live }}</ref> original plans for the Gateway Program did not. Amtrak trains pass through the station, but do not stop there, nor are there plans to include an Amtrak stop.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> In April 2012, Amtrak announced that the project might include a "Bergen Loop" connecting [[Main Line (NJ Transit)|Main Line]], [[Bergen County Line]], [[Pascack Valley Line]] and [[Port Jervis Line]] service<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bowen |first=Douglas John |title=Secaucus Loop idea revived, tied to Gateway Tunnel |magazine=Railway Age |date=June 19, 2013 |url=http://www.railwayage.com/index.php/passenger/commuter-regional/secaucus-loop-proposal-revived-tied-to-gateway-tunnel.html |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143544/https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/commuterregional/secaucus-loop-proposal-revived-tied-to-gateway-tunnel/ |url-status=live }}</ref> to the NEC at Secaucus Junction.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rouse |first=Karen |title=Amtrak's Gateway Proposal includes "Bergen Loop" to NYV |newspaper=The Record |date=April 24, 2012 |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/Amtraks_Gateway_proposal_includes_Bergen_loop_to_NYC.html |access-date=April 30, 2012 |archive-date=April 28, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428013929/http://www.northjersey.com/news/Amtraks_Gateway_proposal_includes_Bergen_loop_to_NYC.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.njspotlightnews.org/video/gateway-tunnel-could-bring-direct-train-service-from-north-jersey-to-nyc/ |title=Gateway Tunnel Could Bring Direct Train Service from North Jersey to NYC |date=April 26, 2012 |website=NJ Spotlight News |access-date=January 26, 2023 |archive-date=December 25, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241225032644/https://www.njspotlightnews.org/video/gateway-tunnel-could-bring-direct-train-service-from-north-jersey-to-nyc/ |url-status=live }}</ref> MTA constituencies are encouraging the agency to include funding for the loop its capital plan.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rife |first=Judy |title=MTA urged to back Amtrak project 1-seat trip for Port riders to Midtown seen |newspaper=Times Herald-Record |date=August 31, 2014 |url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20140831%2FBIZ%2F408310312 |access-date=September 3, 2014 |archive-date=September 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906223221/http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20140831%2FBIZ%2F408310312 |url-status=live }}</ref>

If a loop were built, passengers bound for New York Penn Station would not need to use Secaucus Junction for transfers. Trains using the loop would also increase the capacity demands on the already over-capacity NEC, which the Gateway Program is designed to alleviate. Suburban property owners along the [[Main Line (NJ Transit)|Main Line]]/[[Bergen County Line]] and [[Pascack Valley Line]] would stand to gain economically as property values have increased significantly along commuter rail lines once they were upgraded to offer "single-seat commutes".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/port-authority-commits-to-direct-ride-to-nyc-for-north-jersey-commuters-as-part-of-hudson-river-tunnel-1.1532989 |title=Port Authority rail tunnel plan includes direct ride for North Jersey commuters |last=Maag |first=Christopher |date=March 25, 2016 |website=The Record |access-date=July 26, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325120252/http://www.northjersey.com/news/port-authority-commits-to-direct-ride-to-nyc-for-north-jersey-commuters-as-part-of-hudson-river-tunnel-1.1532989 |archive-date=March 25, 2016}}</ref>

===Tunnels===
[[File:New York City - Pennsylvania Station.jpg|thumb|left|The Gateway Tunnel will join the current right-of-way at the south side (left.)]]

The Gateway Program would build two new tunnels, doubling the rail capacity.<ref name="deis summary">{{Cite web |url=http://hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/00%20Executive%20Summary.pdf |title=Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS) Executive Summary |date=June 2017 |website=hudsontunnelproject.com |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration, New Jersey Transit |access-date=July 10, 2017 |archive-date=December 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215054037/http://hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/00%20Executive%20Summary.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Rp|S-2 to S-3, S-10}}<ref name="deis ch 5B" />{{rp|5B-17}} The current [[North River Tunnels]] allow a maximum of 24 one-way crossings per hour;<ref name="TravelTrends-Aftermath-2006">{{Cite journal |title=NJ Transit's Response to Shifting Travel Demand in the Aftermath of September 11, 2001 |journal=Travel Trends |volume=3 |publisher=The Alan M. Voorhees Transportation Center |location=New Brunswick |date=Fall 2006 |url=http://policy.rutgers.edu/vtc/reports/REPORTS/traveltrends-winter2006.pdf |access-date=March 8, 2011 |quote=NJ TRANSIT financed a new High Density Signal system in conjunction with the Kearny Connection, Montclair Connection and Secaucus Transfer projects that allowed the total number of NJ TRANSIT and Amtrak peak period trains operating in the heavily congested NewarkPSNY corridor to increase from 18 per hour to 23. The new signal system enabled NJ TRANSIT to substantially increase its share of peak hour trains, from 11 (of the prior capacity of 18) to 17 or 18, depending on the hour, of the 23 now available. (The "New Initiatives" agreement anticipated a capacity of 25 trains during the peak hour; however, NJ TRANSIT and Amtrak, through informal agreement, have limited the maximum number of hourly moves to 23 because of the continuing need to "reverse" trains out of New York back to New Jersey to make additional runs. These "reverse moves" cross the path of inbound trains and consume one or two precious peak slots per hour in New York. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720041452/http://policy.rutgers.edu/vtc/reports/REPORTS/traveltrends-winter2006.pdf |archive-date=July 20, 2011 }}</ref><ref name="Amtrak-Fact-Sheet-FY2017">{{cite web |url=https://www.amtrak.com/content/dam/projects/dotcom/english/public/documents/corporate/statefactsheets/NEWJERSEY17.pdf |title=Amtrak Fact Sheet, Fiscal Year 2017, State of New Jersey |publisher=[[Amtrak]] |date=2017 |access-date=January 1, 2018 |page=3 |archive-date=February 6, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206104111/https://www.amtrak.com/content/dam/projects/dotcom/english/public/documents/corporate/statefactsheets/NEWJERSEY17.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> the Gateway proposal would allow an additional 24 trains per hour.<ref name="GPDC-Board-201701">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gatewayprogram.org/content/dam/nec/gdc-board-items-january/2017-01-12-Porcari-GDC-Final.pdf |title=Gateway Program Overview and Update |publisher=Gateway Program Development Corporation |date=January 12, 2017 |first=John D. |last=Porcari |access-date=January 1, 2018 |page=21 |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072421/http://www.gatewayprogram.org/content/dam/nec/gdc-board-items-january/2017-01-12-Porcari-GDC-Final.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

====North River Tunnels====
The North River Tunnels were 102 years old when they were inundated by seawater from Hurricane Sandy in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amtrak Tunnels Flooded During Sandy To Reopen Friday |website=CBS New York |date=November 7, 2012 |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/11/07/amtrak-tunnels-flooded-during-sandy-to-reopen-friday/ |access-date=May 7, 2018 |archive-date=May 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508053850/http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/11/07/amtrak-tunnels-flooded-during-sandy-to-reopen-friday/ |url-status=live }}</ref> If the new Hudson Tunnel is not built, the North River Tunnels will have to be closed one at a time, reducing weekday service below the existing level of 24 trains per hour. Due to the need to provide two-way service on a single track, service would be reduced by over 50 per cent.<ref name=Amtrak-Fact-Sheet-FY2017/> In the best-case scenario, with perfect operating conditions, 9 trains per hour could be provided through the tunnel, or a 63% reduction in service. During the duration of construction, passengers would have to use overcrowded PATH, buses, and ferries to get between New Jersey and New York.<ref name="deis ch 1">{{Cite web |url=http://hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/01%20Purpose%20and%20Need.pdf |title=Hudson Tunnel Project Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS) Chapter 1 Purpose and Need |date=June 2017 |website=hudsontunnelproject.com |access-date=July 10, 2017 |archive-date=July 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730110048/http://hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/01%20Purpose%20and%20Need.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Rp|1–7}} In May 2014, Amtrak CEO Joseph Boardman told the [[Regional Plan Association]] that there was something less than 20 years before one or both of the tunnels would have to be shut down.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rubinstein |first=Dana |title=Clock ticking on Hudson crossings, Amtrak warns |newspaper=Capital |date=May 5, 2014 |url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2014/05/8544757/clock-ticking-hudson-crossings-amtrak-warns |access-date=May 20, 2014 |archive-date=May 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510062536/http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2014/05/8544757/clock-ticking-hudson-crossings-amtrak-warns |url-status=live }}</ref>

As a result of the storm damage and the tunnels' age, component failures regularly occur within the tubes, resulting in frequent delays.<ref name="APNews-Nightmare-2014">{{cite web |title=Sandy-damaged tunnels could cause Amtrak nightmare |website=AP News |date=October 2, 2014 |url=https://www.apnews.com/c3811ff029464ac8be35314417fbfd23 |access-date=May 7, 2018 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507222054/https://www.apnews.com/c3811ff029464ac8be35314417fbfd23 |url-status=live }}</ref> One report in 2019 estimated that the North River Tubes and the Portal Bridge contributed to 2,000 hours of delays between 2014 and 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wanek-Libman |first=Mischa |date=July 23, 2019 |url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/infrastructure/article/21089671/how-bad-are-delays-caused-by-north-river-tunnel-and-portal-bridge-2000-lost-hours-bad |title=How bad are delays caused by North River Tunnel and Portal Bridge? 2,000 lost hours bad. |website=www.MassTransitMag.com |language=en |access-date=July 26, 2019 |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726161856/https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/infrastructure/article/21089671/how-bad-are-delays-caused-by-north-river-tunnel-and-portal-bridge-2000-lost-hours-bad |url-status=live }}</ref> The North River Tunnels need to be repaired without major reductions in weekday service, making it necessary to have new tunnels built. Once the new tunnels open, the two North River Tunnels would close for repairs, one at a time, with the existing level of service maintained. This is because the new tunnel would be located further south–there would be no access to Track 19, and Tracks 9–18 would only have access to the tunnel by the single I ladder-track. Once the new North River Tunnels reopen in 2030, capacity on the line would be doubled. The Hudson Tunnel Project would also allow for resiliency on the Northeast Corridor to be increased, making service along the line more reliable with redundant capacity.<ref name="deis summary" />{{Rp|S-2 to S-3, S-10}}<ref name="deis ch 5B">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/05B%20Transportation%20Services.pdf |title=Hudson Tunnel Project Draft Environmental Impact Study Chapter 5B Transportation Services |date=June 2017 |website=hudsontunnelproject.com |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration, New Jersey Transit |access-date=July 10, 2017 |archive-date=September 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907033656/http://www.hudsontunnelproject.com/documents/deis/05B%20Transportation%20Services.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Rp|5B-17}}

====Hudson Tunnel====
The Gateway Hudson River tunnel, one point of which would be at {{coord|40.75479|-74.01677|display=inline|type:landmark_region:US}}, will travel from a point at [[Weehawken Cove]] under the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]] and its eastern portal south of [[West Side Yard]] in Manhattan.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> Engineering studies for ARC along this route had been deemed unfeasible.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Barbara |first=Philip |title=Planned Hudson River rail tunnel isn't perfect, but it's good |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=April 26, 2009 |url=http://blog.nj.com/njv_guest_blog/2009/04/planned_hudson_river_rail_tunn.html |access-date=March 6, 2011 |quote=One previous ARC design had a new NJ Transit station below Penn Station, which would enable all train platforms to be under one roof. But geologists found softer rock formations from an ancient stream bed that would not provide the necessary structural integrity required of new construction.....But planners found they could not repeat in a built-up city what the Pennsylvania Railroad did when it built the existing tunnel 100 years ago by digging a wide trench through the west side of Manhattan. The only solution was to dig deep – low enough to avoid the historic 90-foot-deep shoreline bulkhead and the New York Subway No. 7 line's extension. From that depth and in a short distance, trains can't reliably rise to make it into Penn Station. After repeated review, it was concluded a spur from the new tunnel was impossible. |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714185021/http://blog.nj.com/njv_guest_blog/2009/04/planned_hudson_river_rail_tunn.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Surveys of properties that would or would not be affected by underground construction at the underground eastern end of the ARC Tunnel had been completed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.arctunnel.com/property/ |title=New York Property Information |year=2011 |website=Access to the Region's Core |publisher=PANYNJ/NJT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303061338/http://www.arctunnel.com/property/ |archive-date=March 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 6, 2011 }}</ref>

In April 2011, $188 million in federal funding was requested for preliminary engineering studies and environmental analysis.<ref name="AMTKseeking" /><ref name="Amstrakseeks">{{cite web |title=Amtrak Seeks $1.3 billion for Gateway Project and Next-Generation High-Speed Rail on NEC |publisher=Amtrak |date=April 4, 2011 |url=http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/BlobServer?blobcol=urldata&blobtable=MungoBlobs&blobkey=id&blobwhere=1249224538367&blobheader=application%2Fpdf&blobhead |access-date=April 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503205942/http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/BlobServer?blobcol=urldata&blobtable=MungoBlobs&blobkey=id&blobwhere=1249224538367&blobheader=application%2Fpdf&blobhead |archive-date=May 3, 2011 }}</ref> On May 2, 2016, the FRA published a Notice of Intent to jointly prepare an [[environmental impact statement]] (EIS) with NJ Transit for the Hudson Tunnel Project under the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA). The EIS will evaluate the potential environmental impacts of a reasonable range of alternatives, including a no-build alternative. As appropriate, FRA and NJ Transit will coordinate with Amtrak and PANYNJ on the EIS.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2016/05/02/2016-10277/environmental-impact-statement-eis-for-the-hudson-tunnel-project-in-hudson-county-new-jersey-and-new |title=Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) for the Hudson Tunnel Project in Hudson County, New Jersey and New York County, New York |date=May 2, 2016 |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration |access-date=May 23, 2016 |archive-date=May 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512171740/https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2016/05/02/2016-10277/environmental-impact-statement-eis-for-the-hudson-tunnel-project-in-hudson-county-new-jersey-and-new |url-status=live }} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

The ARC Tunnel was to be built in three sections: under the Hudson Palisades, under the Hudson River, and under the streets of Manhattan, where it would have dead-ended. The Hudson Tunnel will likely be built along the footprint of the Palisades and river sections, but will enable trains to join the current [[interlocking]] once it emerges. A [[flying junction]] is planned for later stages. This will allow Amtrak and NJT to continue to use the [[East River Tunnels]] and [[Sunnyside Yards]] for staging, storage, and carrying Amtrak NEC trains.<ref name="GatewayPDF" />
The Draft Environmental Impact Study (DEIS) for the Gateway tunnels was issued in June 2017. Four alternatives for alignments under the Hudson River and the Palisades. Option 1 would have the new tunnels run close to the existing tunnels with a ventilation site near the Lincoln Tunnel Helix. This option would have required a construction staging site within the Lincoln Tunnel Helix, thus displacing New Jersey Transit's Weehawken bus storage site, which would have a negative impact on the operation of buses to the Port Authority Bus Terminal. Option 2 would have the new tunnels run further south than the first option, with a shaft site north of 19th Street near JFK Boulevard East. This option would require the acquisition and demolition of an existing multi-story office building to build the shaft site. The third option would be further south, with a shaft site south of 19th Street. This option would preclude the development of a portion of a planned residential development under construction at 800 Harbor Boulevard. The fourth option would be further south with a shaft site south of 18th Street, following the same horizontal alignment identified in the ARC FEIS. Alignment Option 4 was chosen for the build alternative, even though it would have a slightly longer tunnel than the other alternatives. Because of the additional length, there would be additional tunneling costs for this option. The first three options have greater pre-construction risks, meaning that if construction were delayed, the cost difference would be minimized. In addition, Option 4 does not have the issues that the first three options have.<ref name="deis summary" />{{Rp|S-6}}<ref name="deis ch 1" />{{Rp|2–9 to 2–10}}

The new tunnel would be built to comply with the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) 130, Standard for Fixed Guideway Transit and Passenger Rail Systems, with the two tubes connected by cross passages every {{Convert|750|feet|meters}} with fire-rated doors to separate the two tubes.{{Rp|S-9}}<ref name="deis summary" /> The tunnel would be constructed through the use of two tunnel boring machines beneath the river bottom.<ref name="deis summary" />{{Rp|S-11}}

While the Hudson Tunnel Project would double the number of tracks under the Hudson River, it would not result in an increase in rail capacity due to constraints at Penn Station. Penn Station operates at capacity during peak periods, and since it takes a long time for passengers to board and alight trains, trains cannot leave and enter the station as might otherwise be possible. Even with improvements in the station, there are inadequate train storage facilities at Penn, and there is no capacity in the East River Tunnels to allow for trains to be stored during middays at Sunnyside Yard. Without these additional improvements, it is assumed that the same number of trains going between New Jersey and New York today would be operating in 2030, albeit with the additional tunnel capacity.<ref name="deis summary" />{{RP|S-9 to S-10}} The first construction contract relating to the tunnel itself, a contract for stabilizing the riverbed, was awarded in February 2024.<ref name="Simko-Bednarski 2024 v607">{{cite web | last=Simko-Bednarski | first=Evan | title=Gateway commission awards first contract in Hudson River tunnel project | website=New York Daily News | date=February 16, 2024 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/2024/02/16/gateway-project-commission-awards-first-contract-in-hudson-river-tunnel-project/ | access-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240220031316/https://www.nydailynews.com/2024/02/16/gateway-project-commission-awards-first-contract-in-hudson-river-tunnel-project/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Wilson 2024 n533">{{cite web | last=Wilson | first=Colleen | title=Hudson riverbed to be stabilized for Gateway rail tunnel | website=Bergen Record | date=February 16, 2024 | url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2024/02/16/hudson-riverbed-stabilized-gateway-rail-tunnel-project/72627882007/ | access-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240220031316/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2024/02/16/hudson-riverbed-stabilized-gateway-rail-tunnel-project/72627882007/ | url-status=live }}</ref> By mid-2024, the first tunnel boring machine was scheduled to begin digging in late 2024 or early 2025, while a second TBM was to begin digging in 2026. Each TBM was expected to take two years to finish excavating its respective tube.<ref>{{cite web | title=Officials sign off on $6.88 billion grant for Gateway Tunnel | website=Trains | last=Lassen | first=David | date=July 9, 2024 | url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/officials-sign-off-on-6-88-billion-grant-for-gateway-tunnel/ | access-date=July 9, 2024}}</ref> Though tunneling had still not begun by mid-2025, both of the TBMs were nearly fully assembled by then, and work was scheduled to begin in mid-2026.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gottlieb|first=Bryan|title=NYC Gateway Project TBMs Near Completion, on Track for 2026 Tunneling Start|website=Engineering News-Record|date=August 20, 2025|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/61233-nyc-gateway-project-tbms-near-completion-on-track-for-2026-tunneling-start|access-date=August 23, 2025|archive-date=August 22, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250822175217/https://www.enr.com/articles/61233-nyc-gateway-project-tbms-near-completion-on-track-for-2026-tunneling-start|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Spivack|first=Caroline|title=Tunneling to begin in summer 2026 for Hudson River rail tube linking NY and NJ|website=Crain&#039;s New York Business|date=August 21, 2025|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/tunneling-begin-2026-hudson-river-rail-tube-linking-ny-and-nj|access-date=August 23, 2025|archive-date=August 28, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250828065922/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/transportation/tunneling-begin-2026-hudson-river-rail-tube-linking-ny-and-nj|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2026, the Gateway Development Commission hired Traylor–Walsh–Skanska Joint Venture to construct the tunnel for about $1.29 billion.<ref>{{cite web | last=Higgs | first=Larry | title=It's really happening. $1.28B contract awarded to drill the Gateway tunnel under the Hudson | website=nj | date=2026-04-27 | url=https://www.nj.com/news/2026/04/its-really-happening-128b-contract-awarded-to-drill-the-gateway-tunnel-under-the-hudson.html | access-date=2026-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Fazelpoor |first=Matthew |date=April 27, 2026 |title=Gateway awards $1.29B Hudson River Tunnel contract |url=https://njbiz.com/gateway-1-29b-hudson-tunnel-contract-award/ |access-date=April 28, 2026 |work=NJBIZ |archive-date=April 29, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260429111947/https://njbiz.com/gateway-1-29b-hudson-tunnel-contract-award/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Palisades Tunnel====
A [[groundbreaking]] for ARC was held on June 8, 2009,<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=New Jersey Transit |date=June 8, 2009 |title=New Jersey Breaks Ground on Nation's Largest Transit Project |url=http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=PressReleaseTo&PRESS_RELEASE_ID=2516 |access-date=February 13, 2010 |archive-date=June 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627234727/http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=PressReleaseTo&PRESS_RELEASE_ID=2516 |url-status=dead }}</ref> for new underpass at {{Coord|40|45|56|N|74|2|14|W|name=Gateway Palisades Tunnel|display=inline}}, under [[Tonnelle Avenue]] in [[North Bergen]] near the site western portal of the tunnel through [[Bergen Hill|Hudson Palisades]] just south of the [[North River Tunnels]]. The land, which cost $26.3 million, is owned by NJT.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wilshe |first=Brett |title=With ARC tunnel scrapped, NJ Transit officials wonder what to do with $26.3 million worth of North Bergen property |newspaper=The Jersey Journal |date=October 31, 2010 |url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2010/10/with_arc_tunnel_scrapped_nj_tr.html |access-date=February 15, 2011 |archive-date=February 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211161657/http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2010/10/with_arc_tunnel_scrapped_nj_tr.html |url-status=live }}</ref> A tunneling contract for the Palisades Tunnel was awarded on May 5, 2010, to [[Skanska]].<ref name="skanska">{{cite web |title=Skanska to Construct Rail Tunnel in New York for USD 52 M, Approximately SEK 380 M |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100517007289/en/Skanska-Construct-Rail-Tunnel-York-USD-52 |date=May 18, 2010 |publisher=Business Wire |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=July 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708105413/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100517007289/en/Skanska-Construct-Rail-Tunnel-York-USD-52 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Finkelstein |first=Alex |title=Skanska Constructing $258 Million Palisades Tunnel for New Jersey Transit |date=May 18, 2010 |url=http://www.realestatechannel.com/us-markets/commercial-real-estate-1/real-estate-news-skanska-new-jersey-transit-palisades-tunnel-trans-hudson-express-project-skanska-usa-civil-2555.php |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908070846/http://www.realestatechannel.com/us-markets/commercial-real-estate-1/real-estate-news-skanska-new-jersey-transit-palisades-tunnel-trans-hudson-express-project-skanska-usa-civil-2555.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 8, 2012 |access-date=February 19, 2011 }}</ref> Maps indicate this part of the Hudson Tunnel would follow a route to the [[Weehawken, New Jersey|Weehawken]]-[[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] border.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> In October 2012, in an eminent domain case for a property in Weehawken NJ Transit acquired a parcel in the path of the tunnel for $8.5 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |title=NJ Transit still paying price for canceled Hudson River rail tunnel |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=October 16, 2012 |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2012/10/nj_transit_still_paying_price.html |access-date=March 30, 2013 |archive-date=March 22, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322203356/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2012/10/nj_transit_still_paying_price.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Federal funding of $25 million for the completion of an overpass carrying [[U.S. Route 1/9]] above the New Jersey portal was authorized in June 2023,<ref name="Higgs 2023 l462">{{cite web |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=June 23, 2023 |title=Feds give $25M to build N.J. highway bridge that was started and canceled in 2010 |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2023/06/feds-give-25m-to-build-nj-highway-bridge-that-was-started-and-canceled-in-2010.html |access-date=September 12, 2023 |website=nj}}</ref> and the Gateway Development Commission awarded $47.3 million in contracts that September to raise Tonnelle Avenue above the portal.<ref name="nyt-2023-09-11">{{Cite news |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=September 11, 2023 |title=13 Years Later, Construction to Restart on Hudson River Rail Tunnel |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/09/11/nyregion/gateway-amtrak-tunnel.html |access-date=September 12, 2023 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Leggate 2023 n754">{{cite web |last=Leggate |first=James |date=September 12, 2023 |title=Gateway Awards Contracts for Early Work on New Jersey Side of Hudson Rail Tunnel |url=https://www.enr.com/articles/57085-gateway-awards-contracts-for-early-work-on-new-jersey-side-of-hudson-rail-tunnel |access-date=September 12, 2023 |website=Engineering News-Record |archive-date=September 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230921010433/https://www.enr.com/articles/57085-gateway-awards-contracts-for-early-work-on-new-jersey-side-of-hudson-rail-tunnel |url-status=live }}</ref> Work on the Tonnelle Avenue overpass began in November 2023.<ref name="Gainer 2023 z143">{{cite web | last=Gainer | first=Alice | title=Roadway bridge construction for Hudson River tunnel begins in North Bergen, N.J. | website=CBS New York | date=November 30, 2023 | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/highway-bridge-construction-for-hudson-river-tunnel-begins-in-north-bergen-n-j/ | access-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-date=February 20, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240220030835/https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/highway-bridge-construction-for-hudson-river-tunnel-begins-in-north-bergen-n-j/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

===Hudson Yards "tunnel box" and West Side Yard===
[[File:PennStation.jpg|thumb|A "tunnel box" was built in the West Side Yard to preserve a right-of-way for future use.]]
The air rights over the [[West Side Yard]] are being developed as a residential and commercial district on a platform constructed over the yard as part of the [[Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project|Hudson Yards]] project.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rezoning Will Allow Railyard Project to Advance |first=Charles V. |last=Bagli |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/nyregion/22hudson.html |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |date=December 21, 2009 |access-date=December 22, 2009 |archive-date=October 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020152756/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/22/nyregion/22hudson.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MTA Finalizes Hudson Yards Deal |url=http://www.mta.info/news/stories/?story=67 |work=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |date=May 26, 2010 |access-date=May 31, 2010 |archive-date=June 2, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602085420/http://mta.info/news/stories/?story=67 |url-status=live }}</ref> Placing a new Amtrak portal in Manhattan could have conflicted with the Hudson Yards project, which broke ground in late 2012.<ref name="action" /> In February 2013, Amtrak officials said they would commission a project to preserve a right-of-way under Hudson Yards for future use, to be built with $120 million to $150 million in federal funds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sichert |first=Bill |title=Amtrak to construct 'tunnel box' for Hudson River rail project to cross Manhattan development |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=March 5, 2013 |url=http://www.nj.com/somerset/index.ssf/2013/03/amtrak_to_construct_tunnel_box.html |access-date=March 9, 2013 |archive-date=September 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200904022337/https://www.nj.com/somerset/2013/03/amtrak_to_construct_tunnel_box.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Samtani |first=Hiten |title=Related, Amtrak to construct rail tunnel between Manhattan and NJ |publisher=The Real Deal |date=February 26, 2013 |url=http://therealdeal.com/blog/2013/02/26/related-amtrak-to-construct-rail-tunnel-between-manhattan-and-nj/ |access-date=March 9, 2013 |archive-date=March 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305192501/http://therealdeal.com/blog/2013/02/26/related-amtrak-to-construct-rail-tunnel-between-manhattan-and-nj/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |authorlink=Steve Cuozzo |last=Cuozzo |first=Steve |title=Fed money keeps rail tunnel alive |newspaper=The New York Post |date=February 26, 2013 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/realestate/commercial/fed_money_keeps_rail_tunnel_alive_02ScWZ2xkmnE17S2cRty7J |access-date=March 9, 2013 |archive-date=March 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301013535/http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/realestate/commercial/fed_money_keeps_rail_tunnel_alive_02ScWZ2xkmnE17S2cRty7J |url-status=live }}</ref> in June 2013 it was announced that $183 million had been dedicated to the "tunnel box" as part of [[Hurricane Sandy]] recovery funding.<ref name="NJpricetag">{{Cite web |url=http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/13/10/21/nj-faces-hefty-pricetag-for-rail-tunnel-transportation-projects/?p=all |title=NJ Faces Hefty Pricetag for Rail Tunnel, Transportation Projects |last=Magyar |first=Mark J. |date=October 21, 2013 |publisher=NJ Spotlight |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-date=October 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023143650/http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/13/10/21/nj-faces-hefty-pricetag-for-rail-tunnel-transportation-projects/?p=all |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Trans-Hudson Tunnel Gets Some Real Money |work=Transportation Nation |publisher=WNYC |date=May 30, 2013 |url=http://www.wnyc.org/blogs/transportation-nation/2013/may/30/second-trans-hudson-tunnel-gets-some-real-money |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130705190823/http://www.wnyc.org/blogs/transportation-nation/2013/may/30/second-trans-hudson-tunnel-gets-some-real-money |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 5, 2013 |access-date=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hawkins |first=Andrew |title=Hudson train tunnel project gets kickstart |publisher=Crain's |date=May 30, 2013 |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20130530/TRANSPORTATION/130539987 |access-date=January 27, 2014 |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401194554/http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20130530/TRANSPORTATION/130539987 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Construction began on the first phase, from 10th Avenue and 11th Avenue between 31st Street and 33rd Streets, on September 23, 2013, at {{coord|40.754661|N|74.003783|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ny1.com/content/news/189300/west-side-construction-project-may-bring-new-rail-tunnel-pathways-to-hudson-river |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131106164437/http://www.ny1.com/content/news/189300/west-side-construction-project-may-bring-new-rail-tunnel-pathways-to-hudson-river |url-status=dead |title=West Side Construction Project May Bring New Rail Tunnel Pathways To … |date=November 6, 2013 |last=Martinez |first=Jose |archive-date=November 6, 2013 |website=NY1.com |access-date=October 26, 2017}}</ref> The underground concrete casing for the first phase was {{convert|800|ft|m|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide, and about {{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Environmental Assessment for Construction of a Concrete Casing in the Hudson Yards, New York, New York |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration |date=March 2013 |url=http://www.fra.dot.gov/Elib/Document/3050 |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222827/http://www.fra.dot.gov/Elib/Document/3050 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Amtrak awarded [[Tutor Perini]] a $133 million contract to build a section of box tunnel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Contract awarded for New York rail tunnel |publisher=Construction Index |date=September 7, 2013 |url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/contract-awarded-for-new-york-rail-tunnel |access-date=November 26, 2013 |archive-date=December 3, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203090948/http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/contract-awarded-for-new-york-rail-tunnel |url-status=live }}</ref> This portion was completed a year later. Amtrak, NJ Transit, and the MTA applied to the [[Federal Transit Administration]] for a $65 million matching grant for another {{convert|105|ft|m|abbr=on}} long structure to preserve the right-of-way at [[Eleventh Avenue (Manhattan)|11th Avenue]] in Manhattan<ref>{{cite news |last=Higgs |first=Larry |title=Amtrak: New tunnels needed after Sandy damage |newspaper=Asbury Park Press |date=September 1, 2014 |url=http://www.app.com/story/news/traffic/2014/09/01/sandy-amtrak-tunnels/14928539/ |access-date=September 1, 2014 |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016143539/https://www.app.com/story/news/traffic/2014/09/01/sandy-amtrak-tunnels/14928539/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Maag |first=Christopher |title=Signs of life stir for rail tunnel under Hudson |newspaper=The Record |date=September 21, 2014 |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/signs-of-life-stir-for-rail-tunnel-under-hudson-1.1093168 |access-date=September 22, 2014 |archive-date=September 22, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922135612/http://www.northjersey.com/news/signs-of-life-stir-for-rail-tunnel-under-hudson-1.1093168 |url-status=live }}</ref> under a viaduct that was rehabilitated in 2009–2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/11thavenue_viaduct.pdf |title=11th Avenue Viaduct Over LIRR Yard West 30th to West 33rd Streets |publisher=NYC DOT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602160610/http://home2.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/11thavenue_viaduct.pdf |archive-date=June 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rehabilitation of 11th Avenue Viaduct Over LIRR/Amtrak |publisher=Mueser Rutledge Consulting Engineers |url=http://www.mrce.com/media/projects/09344%20Rehabilitation%20of%2011th%20Avenue%20over%20Amtrak.pdf |access-date=September 3, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513060935/http://www.mrce.com/media/projects/09344%20Rehabilitation%20of%2011th%20Avenue%20over%20Amtrak.pdf |archive-date=May 13, 2008 }}</ref> Construction started in December 2014 and was nearing completion {{as of|July 2017|lc=y}}, though funding disputes stalled the tunnel box's completion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Part of Hudson Yards Tunnels Is Nearly Done. Now It Sits, Unused. |website=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |last=Corasaniti |first=Nick |date=July 20, 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/20/nyregion/hudson-yards-tunnels-gateway-project.html |access-date=August 30, 2018 |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831071950/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/20/nyregion/hudson-yards-tunnels-gateway-project.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The tunnel box was substantially complete by November 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190325_0930_LIRR.pdf |title=Long Island Rail Road Committee Meeting – March 2019 |date=March 25, 2019 |website=mta.info |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] |access-date=August 15, 2019 |page=50 |archive-date=May 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524211224/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190325_0930_LIRR.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref> The following phase would extend the casing between 11th and 12th Avenue as the development of Hudson Yards continues westward.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nec.amtrak.com/content/hudson-yard-right-way-preservation-project |title=Hudson Yard Right-of-Way Preservation Project |publisher=Amtrak |language=en |access-date=July 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019104758/http://nec.amtrak.com/content/hudson-yard-right-way-preservation-project |archive-date=October 19, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Work on the concrete tunnel box resumed in November 2023.<ref name=":1" /><ref name="ny1-2023-11-03">{{Cite web |last=Brosnan |first=Erica |date=November 3, 2023 |title=Gateway Tunnel project work begins amid $3.8B in new funding |url=https://ny1.com/nyc/manhattan/news/2023/11/03/gateway-tunnel-project-work-begins-amid--3-8b-in-new-funding |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=[[NY1]] |language=en}}</ref> In July 2025, workers diverted 12th Avenue so they could begin the [[ground freezing]] of the riverbed, which in turn would allow workers to begin digging the tunnel under the river.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nessen |first=Stephen |date=July 9, 2025 |title=Hudson River train tunnel construction to disrupt West Side drivers, cyclists |url=https://gothamist.com/news/hudson-river-train-tunnel-construction-to-disrupt-west-side-drivers-cyclists |access-date=July 11, 2025 |website=Gothamist |archive-date=July 11, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250711162328/https://gothamist.com/news/hudson-river-train-tunnel-construction-to-disrupt-west-side-drivers-cyclists |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ratliff |first=Laura |date=July 10, 2025 |title=West Side commuters, meet your $16 billion construction headache |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/the-hudson-river-train-tunnel-construction-is-already-messing-with-your-west-side-commute-071025 |access-date=July 11, 2025 |website=Time Out New York |archive-date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250715112311/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/news/the-hudson-river-train-tunnel-construction-is-already-messing-with-your-west-side-commute-071025 |url-status=live }}</ref>

To connect the tunnel to Penn Station, extensive track modifications will be required. The profile of several tracks will have to be lowered so that they can meet the grade of the new tunnel tracks at the new portal within A Yard. The I Ladder track, which runs diagonal to the other tracks to provide connections to the platform tracks, would be extended to connect to the new tracks from the tunnel, allowing trains to stop on Tracks 1 through 18. Some tracks within A Yard would be reconfigured. While construction takes place in A Yard, the three trains stored in A Yard and D Yard would be stored in other locations due to the unavailability of storage tracks in those yards. The Empire Line tunnel, near Tenth Avenue, will be modified: 100 feet of that tunnel beneath Tenth Avenue will be lowered so its tracks can connect to the lower track profile in A Yard. This work will be done during weekends over a 20-month period, or through a full closure of the Empire Line tunnel for two to three months. All of this work would take 21 months.<ref name="deis ch 5B" />{{Rp|5B-15 to 5B-16}}

===New York Penn Station===
{{main|New York Penn Station}}

[[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]], the 1968 structure that replaced the [[Pennsylvania Station (1910–1963)|original Pennsylvania Station]] in New York, has been called the "busiest, most congested, passenger transportation facility in North America on a daily basis".<ref name="atlanticcities">{{cite web |last=Jaffee |first=Eric |title=Can Amtrak Afford Its New NYC Home? |newspaper=Atlantic Monthly |date=December 22, 2011 |url=http://www.theatlanticcities.com/commute/2011/12/can-amtrak-afford-its-new-nyc-home/791/ |access-date=December 28, 2011 |archive-date=February 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212120257/http://www.theatlanticcities.com/commute/2011/12/can-amtrak-afford-its-new-nyc-home/791/ |url-status=live }}</ref> It is used by [[Amtrak]], [[New Jersey Transit]], and the [[Long Island Rail Road]] (LIRR), and served by several [[New York City Subway]] lines. Between 1976 and 2010 weekday train movements increased 89%, from 661 to 1,248, reaching what is considered to be capacity.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> In 2010, the station saw 550,000 daily boardings/alightings.<ref name="AMTKproposes" /><ref name="finally?" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Grynbaum |first=Michael M. |title=The Joys and Woes of Penn Station at 100 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |date=October 18, 2010 |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/the-joys-and-woes-of-penn-station-at-100/?scp=2&sq=Penn%20Station%20busiest&st=cse |access-date=February 16, 2011 |archive-date=September 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930185614/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/the-joys-and-woes-of-penn-station-at-100/?scp=2&sq=Penn%20Station%20busiest&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref>

Penn Station is part of the [[Pennsylvania Plaza]] complex that includes [[Madison Square Garden]] (MSG).<ref name="Pennstation" /> In 2013, the [[New York City Council]] voted to extend the MSG Special Permit by up to ten years, in an effort to have the arena move to a different location so that a new station structure can be built in its place.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gould |first=Jessica |date=July 24, 2013 |title=City Council Limits Lease on Madison Square Garden, Makes Way for a New Penn Station |publisher=WNYC |url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/308647-nyc-limits-madison-square-garden-lease-renewal-makes-way-new-penn-station/ |url-status=live |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203175153/http://www.wnyc.org/story/308647-nyc-limits-madison-square-garden-lease-renewal-makes-way-new-penn-station/ |archive-date=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |date=July 25, 2013 |title=Madison Square Garden told to move |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/25/nyregion/madison-square-garden-is-told-to-move.html |url-status=live |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113100634/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/25/nyregion/madison-square-garden-is-told-to-move.html |archive-date=November 13, 2013 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Stephen Jacob |date=August 13, 2013 |title=Vanity Project: Why Fancy Architecture Won't Save Penn Station |newspaper=The New York Observer |url=http://observer.com/2013/08/vanity-project/ |url-status=live |access-date=November 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202233759/http://observer.com/2013/08/vanity-project/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013}}</ref>

====Moynihan Train Hall====
{{main|Moynihan Train Hall}}

[[File:Acela nearing 9th Av jeh.jpg|thumb|NEC passes under the [[James Farley Post Office]], as seen looking southeast at the rear of the building.]]
In the early 1990s, then-New York Senator [[Daniel Moynihan]] championed a proposal to convert the [[James Farley Post Office]] to a train station.<ref name="finally?">{{Cite news |last=Editorial |title=Moynihan Station, Finally? |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |date=February 23, 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/24/opinion/24wed4.html?scp=2&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=October 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027030159/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/24/opinion/24wed4.html?scp=2&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Blumenthal |first=Sidney |title=To the Pennsylvania Station |newspaper=The New York |date=March 14, 1994 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/1994/03/14/1994_03_14_070_TNY_CARDS_000367637 |access-date=February 19, 2011 |archive-date=October 21, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021213340/http://www.newyorker.com/archive/1994/03/14/1994_03_14_070_TNY_CARDS_000367637 |url-status=live }}</ref> Opened in 1912, soon after the original Pennsylvania Station, the landmark building stood across from Penn Plaza and was built over tracks approaching the station from the west.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lueck |first=Thomas J. |title=A $60 Million Step Forward In Rebuilding Penn Station |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |date=November 11, 1999 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/19/nyregion/a-60-million-step-forward-in-rebuilding-penn-station.html?scp=50&sq=Moynihan%20Farley%20Penn&st=cse |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=September 25, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925085514/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/19/nyregion/a-60-million-step-forward-in-rebuilding-penn-station.html?scp=50&sq=Moynihan%20Farley%20Penn&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=No. 7 Subway Extension – Hudson Yards Rezoning and Development Program |publisher=nyc.gov |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/hyards/hy_chap11_g1_fgeis_final.pdf |access-date=February 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102819/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcp/pdf/hyards/hy_chap11_g1_fgeis_final.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref>

In 2010, work began on a $267 million Phase 1. This phase consisted of an expansion of the Long Island Rail Road's underground West End Concourse, which ran under the Farley Building's main entrance, as well as two entrances to the existing Penn Station platforms through the Farley Building on Eighth Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |last=Castillo |first=Alfonso A. |date=February 16, 2010 |title=First phase of Penn Station overhaul fully funded |url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/first-phase-of-penn-station-overhaul-fully-funded-o93992 |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=Newsday |archive-date=February 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204161732/https://www.newsday.com/long-island/first-phase-of-penn-station-overhaul-fully-funded-1.1764909 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Michaelson |first=Juliette |date=February 16, 2010 |title=Moynihan Station Awarded Federal Grant |newspaper=Friends of Moynihan Station |url=http://www.moynihanstation.org/newsite/TIGER_statement_Friends_of_Moynihan_Station.pdf |url-status=dead |access-date=February 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714141034/http://www.moynihanstation.org/newsite/TIGER_statement_Friends_of_Moynihan_Station.pdf |archive-date=July 14, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Strunsky 2012">{{cite web |last=Strunsky |first=Steve |date=May 10, 2012 |title=Multi-million dollar contract awarded for long-planned expansion of New York's Penn Station |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2012/05/multi-million_dollar_contract.html |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=NJ Advance |archive-date=December 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231022550/https://www.nj.com/news/2012/05/multi-million_dollar_contract.html |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[groundbreaking]] ceremony took place on October 18, 2010.<ref>{{cite journal |date=October 18, 2010 |title=New York Penn Station expansion to finally see light of day |url=http://trn.trains.com/en/Railroad%20News/News%20Wire/2010/10/New%20York%20Penn%20Station%20expansion%20to%20finally%20see%20light%20of%20day.aspx |journal=Trains |access-date=October 20, 2010 |archive-date=March 19, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319201054/http://trn.trains.com/en/Railroad%20News/News%20Wire/2010/10/New%20York%20Penn%20Station%20expansion%20to%20finally%20see%20light%20of%20day.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=May 9, 2012 |title=Work to begin on massive Penn Station expansion |publisher=Long Island Business News |agency=Associated Press |url=http://libn.com/2012/05/09/work-to-begin-on-massive-penn-station-expansion/ |access-date=May 9, 2012 |archive-date=May 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512111640/http://libn.com/2012/05/09/work-to-begin-on-massive-penn-station-expansion/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Bagli2">{{Cite news |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |date=October 18, 2010 |title=A Ceremonial Start for Moynihan Station |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/a-ceremonial-start-for-moynihan-station/?scp=1&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |access-date=February 9, 2011 |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714220451/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/18/a-ceremonial-start-for-moynihan-station/?scp=1&sq=Moynihan%20Station&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2012, the PANYNJ announced that a $270 million contract for the first phase, including the concourse expansion under 8th Avenue, had been awarded.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 9, 2012 |title=Work to begin on massive Penn Station expansion |newspaper=Long Island Business News |agency=Associated Press |url=http://libn.com/2012/05/09/work-to-begin-on-massive-penn-station-expansion/ |access-date=May 9, 2012 |archive-date=May 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512111640/http://libn.com/2012/05/09/work-to-begin-on-massive-penn-station-expansion/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Boburg |first=Shawn |date=May 8, 2012 |title=New Amtrak station to relieve rush-hour crowds at Penn Station in first phase of project |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/Moynihan_train_station.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510034909/http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/Moynihan_train_station.html |archive-date=May 10, 2012 |access-date=May 14, 2012 |newspaper=The Record }}</ref> The West End Concourse opened in June 2017.<ref name="Brenzel 20170615">{{cite web |last=Brenzel |first=Kathryn |date=June 15, 2017 |title=First phase of Moynihan Train Hall project opens on Eighth Ave. |url=https://therealdeal.com/2017/06/15/first-phase-of-moynihan-train-hall-project-opens-on-eighth-ave/ |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=The Real Deal New York |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419143636/https://therealdeal.com/2017/06/15/first-phase-of-moynihan-train-hall-project-opens-on-eighth-ave/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Martinez 2017">{{cite web |last=Martinez |first=Jose |date=June 15, 2017 |title=New Penn Station Entrance Part of Bigger Plan to Revamp Rail Hub |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2017/06/15/new-penn-station-entrance-opens |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=Spectrum News NY1 &#124; New York City |archive-date=April 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210422031225/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2017/06/15/new-penn-station-entrance-opens |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Warerkar |first=Tanay |date=June 15, 2017 |title=Penn Station's West End Concourse finally opens to the public |url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/6/15/15807744/penn-station-west-end-concourse-post-office |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=Curbed NY |archive-date=June 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615163346/https://ny.curbed.com/2017/6/15/15807744/penn-station-west-end-concourse-post-office |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Phase 2 consisted of the new train hall in the fully renovated Farley Building. In January 2016, New York governor Cuomo announced plans for a combined Penn-Farley Post Office complex, a project estimated to cost $3 billion.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bagli |first1=Charles V. |last2=Fitzsimmons |first2=Emma G. |date=January 7, 2016 |title=Cuomo Lays Out Renovation Plan for Penn Station and Farley Post Office |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/07/nyregion/cuomo-lays-out-renovation-plan-for-penn-station-and-farley-post-office.html |access-date=May 30, 2016 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=March 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316222635/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/07/nyregion/cuomo-lays-out-renovation-plan-for-penn-station-and-farley-post-office.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=April 22, 2016 |title=Penn Station Renovation – Moynihan – Empire State Station |url=http://therealdeal.com/2016/04/22/who-can-develop-the-new-3b-penn-station-complex/ |access-date=May 30, 2016 |work=The Real Deal New York |archive-date=May 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529025101/http://therealdeal.com/2016/04/22/who-can-develop-the-new-3b-penn-station-complex/ |url-status=live }}</ref> At that time, the project was renamed Moynihan Train Hall.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tangel |first1=Andrew |last2=West |first2=Melanie Grayce |date=January 8, 2016 |title=New Name for Revamped Penn Station Surprises Moynihan Officials, Sparks Debate |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/proposed-name-of-revamped-penn-station-surprises-moynihan-officials-1452277666 |access-date=March 6, 2019 |work=Wall Street Journal |issn=0099-9660 |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306234913/https://www.wsj.com/articles/proposed-name-of-revamped-penn-station-surprises-moynihan-officials-1452277666 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hardt |first=Bob |date=January 7, 2016 |title=NY1 ItCH: Let's Not Rename Moynihan Station |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/political-itch/2016/01/7/ny1-itch--let-s-not-rename-moynihan-station |access-date=March 6, 2019 |website=Spectrum News NY1 &#124; New York City |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306234847/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/political-itch/2016/01/7/ny1-itch--let-s-not-rename-moynihan-station |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2017, a groundbreaking ceremony was held for the Moynihan Train Hall.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Nasa |first1=Rahima |last2=Blain |first2=Glenn |date=August 17, 2017 |title=Cuomo touts $1.6B train hall project next to Penn Station |language=en |work=NY Daily News |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/cuomo-touts-1-6b-train-hall-project-penn-station-article-1.3420953 |access-date=September 6, 2017 |archive-date=September 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906091706/http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/cuomo-touts-1-6b-train-hall-project-penn-station-article-1.3420953 |url-status=live }}</ref> The train hall opened to the public on January 1, 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Re |first=Justine |date=January 1, 2021 |title=Moynihan Train Hall Opens at Penn Station |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2021/01/01/moynihan-train-hall-opens-at-penn-station |access-date=January 1, 2021 |website=www.ny1.com |language=en |archive-date=January 1, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210101152012/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2021/01/01/moynihan-train-hall-opens-at-penn-station |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=January 1, 2021 |title=Moynihan Train Hall Finally Opens in Manhattan |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/moynihan-train-hall-finally-opens-in-manhattan/2806145/ |access-date=December 31, 2020 |website=NBC New York |language=en-US |archive-date=December 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231033127/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/moynihan-train-hall-finally-opens-in-manhattan/2806145/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Penn Station South====
{{distinguish|Penn South}}
[[File:250 W31 New York Terminal Service Plant jeh.jpg|thumb|right|West 31st St., including the New York Terminal Service Plant<ref>{{cite news |title=Pennsylvania Station, New York Terminal Service Plant, 250 West Thirty-first Street, New York, New York County, NY |publisher=HAER |url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/ny1785/ |access-date=November 25, 2014 |quote=…constructed as an integral component of the original Pennsylvania Station complex and served as a power generation and control center for the station, its tracks and signal systems. the facade was designed by McKim Mead & White to complement the exterior of the Pennsylvania Station. While much of the original service equipment has been dismantled or abandoned, some of the original power distribution equipment is still in use... |archive-date=May 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511084109/http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/ny1785/ |url-status=live }}</ref>]]
[[File:John Baptist RCC 210 W31 jeh.jpg|thumb|right|Capuchin Monastery of St John the Baptist, 31st St]]
Plans call for Penn Station South to be located on the block south of the current [[New York Penn Station]] at 31st Street and diagonally across [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth Avenue]] from the post office, on land which is currently privately held.<ref>{{Cite report |title=Penn 2023 Envisioning a new Penn Station, the next Madison Square Garden, and the future of west Midtown |publisher=Regional Plan Association |date=October 17, 2013 |url=http://www.rpa.org/library/pdf/RPA-MAS-Penn-2023.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225712/http://www.rpa.org/library/pdf/RPA-MAS-Penn-2023.pdf |archive-date=December 2, 2013 }}</ref> While the PANYNJ had been acquiring land for ARC along its route, acquisition south of the station has not begun.<ref name="McGeehan" /> It is likely the entire block would be razed and made available for highrise construction after completion of the station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Midtown block would likely get razed for Gateway plan |work=DNAinfo.com |date=February 17, 2011 |last=Colvin |first=Jill |url=http://www.dnainfo.com/20110217/midtown/midtown-block-would-likely-get-razed-for-gateway-plan |access-date=March 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227020459/http://www.dnainfo.com/20110217/midtown/midtown-block-would-likely-get-razed-for-gateway-plan |archive-date=February 27, 2011 }}</ref> Plans call for seven tracks served by four platforms in what will be a [[Railway terminal|terminal]] annex to the entire station complex.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> In April 2011 Amtrak requested $50 million in federal funding for preliminary engineering and environmental analysis.<ref name="AMTKseeking" /><ref name = "Amstrakseeks"/>

In 2014, it was estimated that it would cost $404 million to purchase 35 properties in order to build a new terminal at the location.<ref>{{cite news |last=Higgs |first=Larry |title=Why Amtrak would have to buy $400M in NYC real estate to build new Hudson tunnel |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=October 7, 2014 |url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2014/10/amtrak_has_404_million_hurdle.html |access-date=October 7, 2014 |archive-date=October 9, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009115757/http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2014/10/amtrak_has_404_million_hurdle.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on development guidelines from the [[New York City Planning Commission]], it is estimated that at 2015 prices it would cost between $769 million and $1.3 billion to buy the block bounded to the north and south by 31st and 30th streets, and to the east and west by Seventh and Eighth avenues. Real estate prices are 2½ times higher now than they were in 2012 according to prominent real estate firm [[Cushman & Wakefield]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Maag |first=Christopher |title=Hudson River train tunnel hinges on pricey plan |newspaper=The Record |date=January 17, 2015 |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/hudson-river-train-tunnel-hinges-on-pricey-plan-1.1211136 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316044430/http://archive.northjersey.com/news/hudson-river-train-tunnel-hinges-on-pricey-plan-1.1211136 |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/n-y-c-shrine-to-saint-complicates-amtrak-station-plan-1.1227946 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075801/http://www.northjersey.com/news/n-y-c-shrine-to-saint-complicates-amtrak-station-plan-1.1227946 |title=N.Y.C. shrine to saint complicates Amtrak station plan |last=Maag |first=Christopher |newspaper=The Record |date=January 19, 2015 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

==Related projects==
Other projects in the [[New York metropolitan area]] are planned as part of the NEC [[High speed rail in the United States#Northeast Corridor|Next Generation High Speed Rail]], including the northern and southern approaches to the Gateway Project.<ref>{{cite news |title=Critical Infrastructure Needs on the Northeast Corridor |publisher=Northeast Corridor Infrastructure and Operations Advisory Commission |date=January 2013 |url=http://www.nec-commission.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/necc_cin_20130123.pdf |access-date=January 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035021/http://www.nec-commission.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/necc_cin_20130123.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

===New Brunswick–Trenton high-speed upgrade===
In May 2011, $450 million was dedicated to increase capacity on one of the NEC's busiest segments, a {{convert|24|mi|km|adj=on}} section between [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick]] and [[Trenton, New Jersey|Trenton]], [[New Jersey]]. The planned six-year project will upgrade signals and electrical power systems, including catenary wires, to improve reliability, increase train speeds, and allow more frequent high-speed trains.<ref name="feds">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/05/amtrak_to_receive_800m_from_ca.html |title=Feds steer $450M to N.J. for high-speed rail |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=May 9, 2011 |access-date=May 13, 2011 |newspaper=The Star Ledger |archive-date=February 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210014216/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/05/amtrak_to_receive_800m_from_ca.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2011/05/amtrak_to_receive_nearly_450_m.html |title=Amtrak to receive nearly $450 million in high speed rail funding |last=Thorbourne |first=Ken |date=May 9, 2011 |access-date=May 13, 2011 |newspaper=The Jersey Journal |archive-date=October 18, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018025300/http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2011/05/amtrak_to_receive_nearly_450_m.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/09/floridas-rejected-rail-funds-flow-north/?scp=2&sq=Ray%20Lahood&st=cse |title=Florida's rejected rail funds flow north |last=McGeehan |first=Patrick |date=May 9, 2011 |access-date=May 13, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304173053/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/09/floridas-rejected-rail-funds-flow-north/?scp=2&sq=Ray%20Lahood&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2011, a bill passed by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] threatened funding for the project and others announced at the same time,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/07/house_of_representatives_passe_1.html |title=House passes bill that would divert money from electrical upgrades on N.J. Northeast |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=July 16, 2011 |website=The Star-Ledger |access-date=July 16, 2011 |archive-date=September 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916124727/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/07/house_of_representatives_passe_1.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="divertfunds">{{Cite web |url=http://www.northeastbizalliance.org/blog/ |title=House Vote Jeopardizes Key Northeast Rail Projects |date=July 20, 2011 |website=Back on Track: Northeast |publisher=The Business Alliance for Northeast Mobility |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930021404/http://www.northeastbizalliance.org/blog/ |archive-date=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref> but the money was released the following month.<ref name="obligated">{{Cite web |url=http://www.america2050.org/2011/08/us-dot-obligates-745-million-to-northeast-corridor-rail-projects.html |title=U.S. DOT Obligates $745 Million to Northeast Corridor Rail Projects |last=Schned |first=Dan |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=America 2050 |access-date=November 24, 2011 |archive-date=February 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220101054/http://www.america2050.org/2011/08/us-dot-obligates-745-million-to-northeast-corridor-rail-projects.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The project, along with the purchase of new train sets, is expected to raise speeds on the segment to {{cvt|186|mph}}.<ref name="obligated" /> In September 2012, [[Acela]] test trains hit {{cvt|165|mph}} over the segment.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2012/09/amtrak_train_breaks_us_speed_r.html |title=Amtrak train looks to break U.S. speed record in Northeast Corridor test |last=Frassinelli |first=Mike |date=September 25, 2012 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=December 17, 2012 |archive-date=December 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219175343/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2012/09/amtrak_train_breaks_us_speed_r.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sheehan |first=Rebecca |title=Amtrak tests of Acela express train at 165 mph will not affect commuters |publisher=New Jersey Newsroom |date=September 26, 2013 |url=http://www.newjerseynewsroom.com/science-updates/amtrak-runs-test-at-165-mph |access-date=November 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015350/http://www.newjerseynewsroom.com/science-updates/amtrak-runs-test-at-165-mph |archive-date=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> The track work is one of several projects planned for the "New Jersey Speedway" section of the NEC, which include a new station at [[North Brunswick (NJT station)|North Brunswick, the Mid-Line Loop]] (a flyover for reversing train direction), and the re-construction of [[County Yard]], to be done in coordination with NJT.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.railwayage.com/index.php/passenger/high-performance/amtrak-sprints-toward-a-higher-speed-future.html?channel= |title=Amtrak sprints toward a higher speed future |last=Vantuono |first=William C |date=June 11, 2013 |work=[[Railway Age]] |access-date=January 19, 2014 |archive-date=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140117041947/http://www.railwayage.com/index.php/passenger/high-performance/amtrak-sprints-toward-a-higher-speed-future.html?channel= |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Harold Interlocking and Hutchinson River===
Over 750 LIRR, NJT, and Amtrak trains travel through the [[Harold Interlocking]] every day, causing frequent conflicts and delays.<ref name="obligated" /> In May 2011, a $294.7 million federal grant was awarded to address congestion at the USA's busiest [[rail junction]] and part of the [[Sunnyside Yard]] in [[Queens, New York|Queens]]. The work will allow for a dedicated track to the [[New York Connecting Railroad]] [[right of way (transportation)|right of way]] for Amtrak trains arriving from or bound for [[New England]], thus avoiding NJT and LIRR traffic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://maloney.house.gov/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=2358&Itemid=61 |title=Maloney Hails Federal Grant to Ease Amtrak Delays in NYC, Spur High-Speed Rail in NE Corridor – $294.7 Million Grant to Improve "Harold Interlocking", a Delay-Plagued Junction For Trains in the NE Corridor |date=May 9, 2011 |publisher=Congresswoman Carolyn B. Maloney |access-date=May 13, 2011 |archive-date=September 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928144150/http://maloney.house.gov/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=2358&Itemid=61 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnainfo.com/20110509/midtown/new-york-awarded-350-million-for-highspeed-rail-projects |title=New York Awarded $350 Million for High-Speed Rail Projects |last=Colvin |first=Jill |date=May 9, 2011 |newspaper=DNAinfo.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513083616/http://www.dnainfo.com/20110509/midtown/new-york-awarded-350-million-for-highspeed-rail-projects |archive-date=May 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=May 13, 2011 }}</ref> A new [[flying junction]] will allow Amtrak trains to travel through the interlocking separately from LIRR and NJ Transit trains on their way to Sunnyside.<ref name="obligated" /> Financing for the project was jeopardized when the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] voted in July 2011 to divert the money to unrelated projects,<ref name="divertfunds" /> but funds were later obligated so that work on the project could begin in 2012.<ref name="obligated" /> Some of the interlocking improvement projects are complete as of early 2023, while several other projects are projected for completion by late 2025.<ref>{{cite report |title=Milestone Report; Network Expansion—Regional Investments |url=http://dsearch.mta.info/ibi_apps/WFServlet?IBIF_ex=capitaldashboard_live/milestone_report_pf.fex&AGENCY=G&CATEGORY=All&PHASE=All&TIMELINE=T3&SCHEDSTAT=TL&CATDES=All%20Categories |access-date=February 8, 2023 |publisher=MTA}}</ref>

Amtrak applied in 2011 for $15 million for the environmental impact studies and preliminary engineering design to examine replacement options for the more than 100-year-old, low-level movable [[Pelham Bay Bridge]] over the [[Hutchinson River]] in [[the Bronx]]. The goal is for a new bridge to support expanded service and speeds up to 110&nbsp;mph (177&nbsp;km/h).<ref name="Amstrakseeks"/> In August 2022, the FRA awarded a $4.5 million grant to Amtrak for the bridge replacement project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biden Administration, USDOT Announce Over $233 Million in Grants to Upgrade Intercity Passenger Rail Service |url=https://railroads.dot.gov/newsroom/press-releases/biden-administration-usdot-announce-over-233-million-grants-upgrade-0 |date=August 18, 2022 |publisher=FRA |access-date=August 24, 2023 |archive-date=August 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230824051005/https://railroads.dot.gov/newsroom/press-releases/biden-administration-usdot-announce-over-233-million-grants-upgrade-0 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2023, Amtrak applied for additional FRA grants to support multiple improvement projects in the Northeast Corridor, including additional work on the Pelham Bay Bridge project.<ref name="Toll 2023 c886">{{cite web | last=Toll | first=Beth | title=Amtrak Applies for $7.3 Billion in Federal Grants to Advance Northeast Corridor Infrastructure Upgrades | website=Amtrak Media | date=June 5, 2023 | url=https://media.amtrak.com/2023/06/amtrak-applies-for-7-3-billion-in-federal-grants-to-advance-northeast-corridor-infrastructure-upgrades/ | access-date=August 24, 2023 | archive-date=August 11, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811083111/https://media.amtrak.com/2023/06/amtrak-applies-for-7-3-billion-in-federal-grants-to-advance-northeast-corridor-infrastructure-upgrades/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="International 2023 m101">{{cite web | title=Amtrak applies for federal grants to expand services | website=Railway Gazette International | date=June 7, 2023 | url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/passenger/amtrak-applies-for-federal-grants-to-expand-services/64271.article | access-date=August 24, 2023 | archive-date=September 21, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230921114056/https://www.railwaygazette.com/passenger/amtrak-applies-for-federal-grants-to-expand-services/64271.article | url-status=live }}</ref>

===Subway service===
While not part of the Gateway Project, Amtrak's announcement included a proposal to extend the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) [[7 Subway Extension]] three blocks east to New York Penn Station from the current station at [[34th Street (IRT Flushing Line)|11th Avenue and 34th Street]]. This would provide service to the [[Javits Convention Center]] and a one-seat ride to [[Grand Central Terminal]], the city's other major train terminal on the East Side of Manhattan at 42nd Street.<ref name="GatewayPDF" /> Shortly before the introduction of Gateway, the [[New York City Economic Development Corporation]] voted to budget up to $250,000 for a [[feasibility study]] of a [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]] tunnel for an extension to [[Secaucus Junction]] awarded to [[Parsons Brinckerhoff]], a major engineering firm that had been working on the ARC tunnel.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://transportationnation.org/2011/02/04/city-finally-puts-behind-subway-to-new-jersey/ |title=City finally puts $ behind subway to New Jersey |last=Bernstein |first=Andrea |date=February 4, 2011 |publisher=Transportation Nation |access-date=February 7, 2011 |archive-date=February 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206082530/http://transportationnation.org/2011/02/04/city-finally-puts-behind-subway-to-new-jersey/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/48185181/No-7-Extension-Executive-Committee-Item-Final-Draft-2 |title=No. 7 Line Extension to Secaucus Consultant Services |last=New York City Economic Development Commission |date=February 2, 2011 |publisher=scribd.com |format=PDF |access-date=February 7, 2011 |archive-date=November 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106102528/http://www.scribd.com/doc/48185181/No-7-Extension-Executive-Committee-Item-Final-Draft-2 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2011, NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg reiterated his support for the NJ extension, estimated to cost around $10 billion and take ten years to complete, indicating that he would give approval by the end of his third term in 2013. Environmental-impact studies and a full business plan are required before the proposal proceeds.<ref>{{Cite web |title=N.Y. mayor Bloomberg supports extending No. 7 subway into N.J. |date=October 26, 2011 |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/10/new_york_mayor_michael_bloombe.html |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |access-date=November 22, 2011 |archive-date=November 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128053114/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/10/new_york_mayor_michael_bloombe.html |url-status=live }}</ref> It was likely that the two projects—Gateway and the subway extension—would have been in competition for funding.<ref name="ok15m">{{Cite web |last=Higgs |first=Larry |title=Obama expected to OK $15M for tunnel project between Secaucus and New York – Amtrak tunnel vs. extended subway to Secaucus showdown likely |date=November 19, 2011 |url=http://www.app.com/article/20111118/NJNEWS/311180048/Senate-allots-15M-for-study-on-rail-tunnel |newspaper=Asbury Park Press |access-date=November 23, 2011}}</ref>

In April 2012, citing budget considerations, the director of the MTA effectively scuttled the project and said that it was doubtful the extension would be built in the foreseeable future, suggesting that the Gateway Project was a much more likely solution to congestion at Hudson River crossings.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Haughney |first=Christine |title=MTA Chief rules out subway line to New Jersey |date=April 3, 2012 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/04/nyregion/transit-agency-chief-rules-out-new-york-new-jersey-subway.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=7%20subway%20extension&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=April 4, 2012 |archive-date=August 18, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818071515/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/04/nyregion/transit-agency-chief-rules-out-new-york-new-jersey-subway.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=7%20subway%20extension&st=cse |url-status=live }}</ref> The report was released in April 2013.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/04/plan_to_extend_no_7_city_subwa.html |title=Plan to extend No. 7 subway from NYC to New Jersey could be back on track |last=Frasinelli |first=Mike |date=April 10, 2013 |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=April 10, 2013 |archive-date=December 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215175828/https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/04/plan_to_extend_no_7_city_subwa.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/NY_No_7_Subway_to_Secaucus.html |title=Report: Extending NY No. 7 subway line to Secaucus would accommodate commuter demand |last=Rouse |first=Karen |date=April 10, 2013 |work=The Record |access-date=April 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413011350/http://www.northjersey.com/news/NY_No_7_Subway_to_Secaucus.html |archive-date=April 13, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In a November 2013 ''Daily News'' opinion article, the president of the Real Estate Board of New York and the chairman of [[Edison Properties]] called for the line to be extended to Secaucus in tunnels to be shared with the Gateway Project.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/extend-7-train-secaucus-article-1.1504464 |title=Let's extend the 7 train to Secaucus After the far West Side, the next stop on the 7 should be across the river |last1=Gottesman |first1=Jerry |date=November 4, 2013 |work=Daily News |access-date=November 4, 2013 |last2=Spinola |first2=Steven |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201160413/https://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/extend-7-train-secaucus-article-1.1504464 |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2013, the [[New Jersey Assembly]] passed a Resolution 168<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.njleg.state.nj.us/2012/Bills/AR/168_I1.PDF |title=AN ASSEMBLY RESOLUTION supporting the extension of the New York City IRT Flushing Line into the State of New Jersey. |date=May 13, 2013 |website=ASSEMBLY RESOLUTION No. 168 STATE OF NEW JERSEY 215th LEGISLATURE |publisher=New Jersey Legislature |access-date=November 26, 2013 |archive-date=September 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919135250/https://www.njleg.state.nj.us/2012/Bills/AR/168_I1.PDF |url-status=dead}}</ref> supporting the extension of the line to [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] and Secaucus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/11/no_7_expansion.html#incart_river_default |title=Committee green lights expansion of NYC subway to Hoboken |last=Brenzel |first=Kathryn |date=November 26, 2013 |website=The Star-Ledger |access-date=November 26, 2013 |archive-date=November 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105213817/https://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/11/no_7_expansion.html#incart_river_default |url-status=live }}</ref>

